{"title_page": "Tom Malinowski", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Tom Malinowski\n| image               = Tom Malinowski, official portrait, 116th congress.jpg\n| state               = [[New Jersey]]\n| district            = {{ushr|NJ|7|7th}}\n| term_start          = January 3, 2019\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Leonard Lance]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]\n| president1          = [[Barack Obama]]\n| deputy1             = [[Virginia L. Bennett]]\n| term_start1         = April 3, 2014\n| term_end1           = January 20, 2017\n| predecessor1        = [[Michael Posner (lawyer)|Michael Posner]]\n| successor1          = [[Robert Destro]]\n| birth_date          = {{nowrap|{{birth date and age|1965|9|23}}}}\n| birth_place         = [[S\u0142upsk]], [[Poland]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| education           = [[University of California, Berkeley]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[St Antony's College, Oxford]] ([[Master of Philosophy|MPhil]])\n| website             = {{url|malinowski.house.gov|House website}}\n| birth_name          = Tomasz P. Malinowski\n}}\n'''Tomasz P. Malinowski''' (born September 23, 1965)<ref name=\"AllGov\"/> is an  [[United States|American]] politician and diplomat who is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]]. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he previously served as [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]] in the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]]. Malinowski was first elected in [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections|2018]], defeating [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] incumbent [[Leonard Lance]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski Declares|url=https://www.insidernj.com/press-release/tom-malinowski-declares-candidacy-7th-congressional-district/|publisher=InsiderNJ|date=October 2, 2017|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New Jersey Primary Election Results |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/05/us/elections/results-new-jersey-primary-elections.html |accessdate=8 August 2018 |publisher=New York Times |date=June 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMalinowski was born in [[S\u0142upsk]], Poland, and lived in [[Brwin\u00f3w]] until he left the country at the age of six with his mother, Joanna, who married [[Blair Clark]]. He was raised in [[Princeton, New Jersey]], and graduated from [[Princeton High School (New Jersey)|Princeton High School]] in 1983, where he wrote for the school newspaper ''The Tower'' and was an intern in the office of Senator [[Bill Bradley]].<ref name=\"AllGov\">{{cite web|title=Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor: Who Is Tom Malinowski?|url=http://www.allgov.com/news/appointments-and-resignations/assistant-secretary-of-state-for-democracy-human-rights-and-labor-who-is-tom-malinowski-130721?news=850617|publisher=AllGov|date=July 21, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[political science]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]], in 1987 and a [[Master of Philosophy]] from [[St Antony's College, Oxford]], in 1991, where he was a [[Rhodes Scholar]].<ref name=\"AllGov\"/><ref name=\"State\">{{cite web|title=Tom Malinowski|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/224368.htm|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=April 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nMalinowski began his government career as a special assistant for Senator [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] in 1988. After attending Oxford, Malinowski worked for the [[Institute for Human Sciences]] in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]], and later as a research assistant for the [[Ford Foundation]] in 1993.<ref name=\"State\"/> From 1994 to 1998, Malinowski was a speechwriter for secretaries of state [[Warren Christopher]] and [[Madeleine Albright]], as well as a member of the [[Policy Planning Staff (United States)|Policy Planning Staff]] at the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]].<ref name=\"OpenSecrets\"/> From 1998 to 2001, Malinowski served as senior director on the [[United States National Security Council|National Security Council]] at the [[White House]], where he oversaw the drafting of President [[Bill Clinton]]'s foreign policy speeches and [[strategic communications]] efforts around the world.<ref name=\"State\"/><ref name=\"OpenSecrets\"/>\n\n==Human Rights Watch==\nFrom 2001 to 2013, Malinowski was a lobbyist for [[Human Rights Watch]].<ref name=\"State\"/><ref name=\"OpenSecrets\">{{cite web|title=Malinowski, Tom|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/revolving/rev_summary.php?id=78011|publisher=[[Center for Responsive Politics]]|date=April 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=twsPolitico0099/> In this position, he advocated for terrorists' rights during the [[War on Terror]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scher |first1=Brent |title=NJ Dem Tom Malinowski Tries and Fails to Defend Record of \u2018Lobbying for Terrorist Rights\u2019|url=https://freebeacon.com/politics/nj-dem-tom-malinowski-tries-fails-to-defend-record-of-lobbying-for-terrorist-rights/|publisher=[[The Washington Free Beacon]]|date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> Going as far as to say that [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay]] should be shut down.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Malinowski |first1=Tom |title=Four Good Reasons Why Guantanamo Should Be Closed|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2006/11/22/four-good-reasons-why-guantanamo-should-be-closed# |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=November 22, 2006}}</ref> Malinowski also campaigned against American support of the Israeli military. Malinowski opposed the United States supplying the Israeli Defense Forces with cluster munitions and asked then-Senator [[Hillary Clinton]] to not support Israel\u2019s construction of an \u2018illegal\u2019 wall in the West Bank.<ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |title=Human Rights Watch Lobbying Activity|url=https://freebeacon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Screen-Shot-2018-07-20-at-3.00.16-PM.png |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Malinowski |first1=Tom |title=Human Rights watch Lobbying Activity|url=https://freebeacon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Screen-Shot-2018-07-20-at-3.04.26-PM.png |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\n== Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor ==\nMalinowski was seen by some<ref name=\"Wapo3\">{{cite web|title=Nonprofit Groups Seeking Exceptions to Lobby Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/21/us/politics/21lobby.html|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=April 20, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Wapo4\">{{cite web|title=The Good Lobbyist|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/23/opinion/23thu3.html?mcubz=2|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=April 22, 2006}}</ref> as a likely nominee for [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]] but his previous registration as a lobbyist while at Human Rights Watch necessitated a waiver from the President. On July 8, 2013, during President Obama's second term, Malinowski was nominated to serve as [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]].<ref>{{cite web|title=President Obama Announces More Key Administration Posts|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/07/08/president-obama-announces-more-key-administration-posts|publisher=[[White House]]|date=July 8, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=White House hires lobbyist Malinowski|last=Heil|first=Emily|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/in-the-loop/post/white-house-taps-tom-malinowski-for-human-rights-post/2013/07/09/1395416e-e8a3-11e2-a301-ea5a8116d211_blog.html|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=July 9, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski testified before the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]] on September 24, 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement for the Record by Tom Malinowski, Nominee for Assistant Secretary of State|url=http://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Malinowski.pdf|publisher=[[United States Senate]]|date=September 24, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> and was confirmed by the [[U.S. Senate]] on April 2, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senate confirms State Dept. nominee|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/04/09/senate-confirms-state-dept-nominee/|work=[[Washington Blade]]|date=April 9, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Senate Confirms Tom Malinowski as New Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor|url=http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/press-release/senate-confirms-tom-malinowski-new-assistant-secretary-state-democracy-human-rights|publisher=[[Human Rights First]]|date=April 2, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski confirmed at DRL|url=http://www.demdigest.net/malinowski-confirmed-drl/|publisher=Democracy Digest|date=April 4, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> According to columnist [[Jennifer Rubin (journalist)|Jennifer Rubin]], Malinowski was praised in 2014 by leaders from both parties for his defense of human rights and his work toward ending torture.<ref name=twsWashPost040>Washington Post, Jennifer Rubin, February 21, 2014, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/right-turn/wp/2014/02/21/free-tom-malinowksi/ Free Tom Malinowski], Retrieved May 23, 2018, \"...Tom is widely respected for the indispensable role he has played in defense of human rights and fundamental freedoms, from ending torture to advancing democracy ... He received wide support from Democrats and Republicans who have been united in their criticism of the administration\u2019s ... attitude toward human rights....</ref>\n\nWhile working in the State Department, Malinowski spearheaded efforts to assist persecuted religious minorities targeted by [[ISIS]] in [[Iraq]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A/S Malinowski Briefs Congressional Leaders on ISIL\u2019s Persecution of Religious Minorities in Iraq and Syria=|url=https://geneva.usmission.gov/2014/09/12/as-malinowski-briefs-congressional-leaders-on-isils-persecution-of-religious-minorities-in-iraq-and-syria/|publisher=United States of America Geneva Mission|date=September 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski Testimony|url=https://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Malinowski_Testimony.pdf|publisher=[[U.S. Senate]]|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> He also oversaw efforts to sanction [[North Korea]]n officials for human rights abuses and increase the flow of uncensored information into the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. compiling list of North Korea human rights violators|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2016/04/27/US-compiling-list-of-North-Korea-human-rights-violators/8071461768502/|publisher=[[UPI]]|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanctions on N.K. leader 'just the start,' more blacklisting to come: senior U.S. diplomat|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2016/07/08/0401000000AEN20160708001200315.html| publisher=[[Yonhap]]|date=July 8, 2016}}</ref> He led State Department efforts to defend the [[LGBT]] community around the world and oversaw the appointment of the first [[Randy W. Berry|Special Envoy for LGBT rights]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Support for Gay Rights in Africa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/29/opinion/support-for-gay-rights-in-africa.html?mcubz=1&mtrref=undefined&assetType=opinion|publisher=|date=December 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Special Envoy for LGBT Rights|url=http://www.hrc.org/blog/welcome-to-the-special-envoy-for-lgbt-rights|publisher=[[Human Rights Campaign]]|date=February 27, 2015}}</ref> Malinowski backed [[United Nations]]' efforts to investigate possible [[Alleged war crimes during the final stages of the Sri Lankan Civil War|war crimes]] committed during the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. to Support Sri Lanka Plan to Investigate War Crimes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/27/world/asia/united-states-supports-sri-lanka-investigation-of-war-crimes.html?mtrref=undefined|publisher=[[NY Times]]|date=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He also worked on decreasing civilian casualties from US military operations in the [[Middle East]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Obama\u2019s New Executive Order Increases Drone Transparency, Official Says|url=https://www.washingtonreport.me/2016-august/september/obamas-new-executive-order-increases-drone-transparency-official-says.html|publisher=[[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]]|date=August 2016}}</ref> and assisted with sanctioning Russian officials for [[Magnitsky Act|human rights abuses]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Five Russians blacklisted for alleged human rights abuses|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/five-russians-blacklisted-for-human-rights-abuses/2017/01/09/1b00068c-d6b6-11e6-9f9f-5cdb4b7f8dd7_story.html|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=January 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Malinowski and Omar in 2019.png|thumb|Malinowski with [[Ilhan Omar]] in [[Washington DC]], 2019]]\nIn July 2014, Malinowski was [[persona non grata|expelled]] by [[Bahrain]]'s [[Government of Bahrain|government]] after meeting with members of an opposition group in the course of a scheduled visit.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|title=US diplomat Tom Malinowski expelled from Bahrain|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-28204511|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bahrain: U.S. diplomat 'unwelcome and should immediately leave'|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/07/08/world/meast/bahrain-us-diplomat-unwelcome/|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=July 8, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bahrain expels top US diplomat after meeting with main opposition group|url=https://www.rt.com/news/171084-bahrain-expels-us-diplomat/|publisher=[[RT (TV network)|RT]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> The foreign ministry of Bahrain argued that Malinowski's meeting improperly intervened in the country's affairs but noted the incident would not affect [[Bahrain\u2013United States relations]].<ref name=\"BBC\"/> The [[U.S. State Department]] released a statement of concern about the actions while [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]] called Bahrain's actions unacceptable and contrary to diplomatic protocol.<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite web|last=Schwartz|first=Felicia|title=Tension Between Bahrain and U.S. Continues Over Diplomat's Expulsion|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tension-between-bahrain-and-u-s-continues-over-diplomats-expulsion-1405387624|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=July 14, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Statement on the Decision by the Government of Bahrain To Find Assistant Secretary Malinowski Persona Non Grata and To Expel Him From Bahrain|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2014/07/228839.htm|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski returned to the country in December 2014 with the [[Anne W. Patterson|assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern affairs]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gordon|first=Michael|title=Expelled U.S. Official to Return to Bahrain|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/03/world/middleeast/bahrain-us-human-rights-official-tom-malinowski.html?_r=0|work=[[New York Times]]|date=December 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Press Availability with A/S Tom Malinowski and A/S Anne Patterson|url=http://bahrain.usembassy.gov/pas-120414.html|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=December 4, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414204305/http://bahrain.usembassy.gov/pas-120414.html|archivedate=April 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the end of his tenure at the State Department, Malinowski joined fellow former Obama officials to lobby Congress in an effort to prevent the [[Trump Administration]] from lifting the [[International sanctions during the Ukrainian crisis|sanctions]] on [[Russia]] following its [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|invasion of Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Diplomats: Trump Team Sought to Lift Sanctions on Russia|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/former-diplomats-trump-team-sought-lift-sanctions-russia-n767406|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=June 1, 2017}}</ref> He criticized [[Donald Trump]] for having an \"obscene fondness\" for the world's tyrants and for instituting a \"complete departure from decades of American tradition.\"<ref name=twsPolitico0099>Politico magazine, Susan B. Glasser, June 19, 2017, [https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/06/19/tom-malinowski-man-who-argued-with-dictators-215278 The Man Who Argued With Dictators: Tom Malinowski spent years trying to get President Obama to care more about human rights. Now, he\u2019s figuring out what to do with a president who doesn\u2019t seem to care at all.], Retrieved May 24, 2018, \"...Malinowski spent the past few years pushing Obama from the inside on human rights ... former Washington director of Human Rights Watch ... leading the resistance from the outside to Trump and what he calls his \u201cobscene\u201d fondness for the world\u2019s tyrants....\"</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\nOn October 2, 2017, Malinowski announced his candidacy for U.S. Congress in [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]] in the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kamisar|first1=Ben|title=Obama State Department official to run for House in NJ|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/353408-obama-state-department-official-to-run-for-house-in-nj|accessdate=16 May 2018|publisher=The Hill|date=October 2, 2017}}</ref> He decided to run for Congress after the [[2016 United States presidential election|November 2016 election of Donald Trump]], which he saw as an indication that America was in \"deep trouble.\"<ref name=twsBloomberg445>Albert R. Hunt, May 2, 2018, Bloomberg News, [https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-05-02/democratic-house-candidates-look-mighty-familiar Some Democratic Candidates Look Mighty Familiar], Retrieved May 15, 2018, \"... Malinowski, an assistant secretary of State for President Obama and a State Department official under Clinton ... America, he believes, \"is in deep trouble.\"...\"</ref> Malinowski said he decided to run for office because of what he called the Trump administration's \"effort to take down the Affordable Care Act with no viable replacement. It was the Muslim ban, and attacks on immigrants, it was the tearing up of alliances and commitments internationally. It was the taking down of environmental protections, it was refusing to invest in infrastructure.\"<ref name=\"twsNBCWash11\">May 27, 2018, NBC News Washington (Channel 4), [https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/politics/Former-Obama-Staffers-Elections-483805841.html Fired Up by Trump, Dozens of Former Obama Staffers Run for Office: The surge of Democratic candidates with ties to Obama has the potential to fill state and federal legislatures with like-minded allies], Retrieved May 30, 2018, \"...it was the effort to take down the Affordable Care Act with no viable replacement...\"</ref>\n\nMalinowski supports the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] and criticized the Republican Party for \"whittling away at the Affordable Care Act year after year.\"<ref name=twsInsiderNJ44>Insider New Jersey, May 12, 2018, Staff writer, [https://www.insidernj.com/cd7-democratic-challenger-malinowski-formally-opens-main-headquarters-pallone/ CD7 Democratic Challenger Malinowski Formally Opens his Main Headquarters with Pallone], Retrieved May 14, 2018, \"... He\u2019ll fight to protect the Affordable Care Act.....\"</ref>  He supports raising the minimum wage to $15 per hour as well as enhanced collective bargaining rights and protections for workers.<ref name=twsNJGlobe11/>  Malinowski sees the Democratic Party, in contrast to the GOP, as promoting fiscal responsibility, law enforcement, family values, and patriotism.<ref name=\"twsWashPost0786\">E. J. Dionne, July 15, 2018, Washington Post, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/does-the-blue-wave-start-in-jersey/2018/07/15/db44a0b2-86e4-11e8-8f6c-46cb43e3f306_story.html?wpisrc=nl_headlines&wpmm=1 Does the blue wave start in Jersey?], Retrieved July 16, 2018</ref>\n\n[[File:Candidate for Congress NJ-7th Tom Malinowski at campaign headquarters speaking with a voter.jpg|thumb|upright|Malinowski at his campaign headquarters in [[Martinsville, New Jersey]]]]\nHis endorsements included the Hunterdon County Democratic Committee<ref name=\"twsNJHills41\">April 27, 2018, New Jersey Hills, [http://www.newjerseyhills.com/hunterdon_review/news/first-lady-tammy-murphy-to-speak-at-county-democratic-brunch/article_a25ed6e9-39ca-56e0-a286-f38ca8e86f59.html First Lady Tammy Murphy to speak at county Democratic brunch on Sunday, April 29], Retrieved May 15, 2018, \"...Tom Malinowski ... endorsed by the HCDC ...\"</ref> and the [[Communications Workers of America]].<ref name=\"twsNJGlobe11\">David Wildstein, April 23, 2018, New Jersey Globe, [https://newjerseyglobe.com/congress/cwa-endorses-malinowski/ CWA Endorses Malinowski], Retrieved May 15, 2018</ref> On June 5, 2018, he faced social worker Peter Jacob and lawyer Goutam Jois.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Jersey's 7th Congressional District election, 2018|url=https://ballotpedia.org/New_Jersey%27s_7th_Congressional_District_election,_2018|accessdate=8 May 2018|publisher=Ballotpedia}}</ref> He defeated Jacob and Jois, receiving 66.8% of the vote and winning all counties in the district<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-jersey-house-district-7-primary-election|title=New Jersey Primary Election Results: Seventh House District|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njelections.org/assets/pdf/election-results/2018/2018-official-primary-results-us-house.pdf|title=Candidates for House of Representatives For PRIMARY ELECTION 06/05/2018 Election,|last=|first=|date=July 20, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Malinowski went onto to defeat incumbent Republican [[Leonard Lance]].\n\nMalinowski criticized Lance, saying he \"shifted to the right when he was scared of the [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] and he's moving to the left when he's scared of his increasingly moderate and energized constituents.\"<ref name=\"twsNJcom441\">Jonathan D. Salant, May 14, 2018, NJ.com, [http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/05/how_njs_most_endangered_congressman_is_trying_to_w.html This N.J. Republican is in big trouble because of Trump. Here's what he's doing about it.], Retrieved May 15, 2018</ref> On November 6, Malinowski won the election, receiving 51.7% of the vote. While Malinowski and Lance each carried three of the six counties in the district, Malinowski won the district's shares of Somerset and Union counties by a combined 22,300 votes, more than the overall margin of 16,200 votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-jersey-house-district-7|title=New Jersey\u2019s Seventh House District Election Results: Tom Malinowski vs. Leonard Lance|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njelections.org/assets/pdf/election-results/2018/2018-official-general-election-results-us-house.pdf|title=Official List Candidates for House of Representatives For GENERAL ELECTION 11/06/2018 Election|last=|first=|date=December 3, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> When he took office in January 2019, he became the first Democrat to represent the 7th and its predecessors since 1961.\n\nOn February 26, 2020, Malinowski stated that he would \u201cabsolutely\u201d support [[Bernie Sanders]] if he were the Democratic Presidential nominee.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mascaro |first1=Lisa |title=Pelosi urges Democratic unity amid Sanders\u2019 campaign surge |url=https://apnews.com/7ef003d3d777ba44bb4e24fed66809f8 |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=The Associated Press |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n\n* [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|'''Committee on Foreign Affairs''']]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism|Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|'''Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure''']]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n\n=== Caucus memberships ===\n* '''[[LGBT Equality Caucus]]'''\n* '''[[New Democrat Coalition]]'''\n* '''End Corruption Caucus'''<ref name=\"Malinowski Press Release 2020.01.21\">{{cite web |title=Representative Malinowski Leads Fight To End Corruption in Washington |url=https://malinowski.house.gov/media/press-releases/representative-malinowski-leads-fight-end-corruption-washington |website=Tom Malinowski Congressional Web Site |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Congressman Max Rose Press Release 2020.01.16\">{{cite web |title=10 Years After Disastrous Citizens United Decision, Rose, Porter, Freshmen Dems Launch New \u2018End Corruption\u2019 Caucus |url=https://maxrose.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=2450 |website=Max Rose Congressional Web Site |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===COVID-19===\nMalinowski joked during an April 2020 livestream with constituents that he would withhold shipments of [[Lysol]] disinfectant to the state of [[Kentucky]] until [[Senate Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]], relents in his opposition to Democrat-backed vote-by-mail measures amid the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]]. He was referring to a [[Reckitt Benckiser]] manufacturing plant located in [[Hillsborough Township, New Jersey|Hillsborough Township]] which produces 100% of the United States' supply of Lysol disinfectant.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Snowflack |first1=Fred |title=Kentucky Strikes Back at Malinowski |url=https://www.insidernj.com/kentucky-strikes-back-at-malinowski/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Insider NJ |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Saxena |first1=Vivek |title=\u2018We make 100 percent\u2019: NJ Dem \u2018jokes\u2019 about withholding Lysol products to strongarm Mitch McConnell |url=https://www.bizpacreview.com/2020/04/10/we-make-100-percent-nj-dem-jokes-about-withholding-lysol-products-to-strongarm-mitch-mcconnell-906928 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Biz Pac Review |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"There\u2019s nothing funny about a member of Congress threatening to withhold vital supplies from Kentuckians during a deadly outbreak,\u201d [[Republican Party of Kentucky]] spokesman Mike Lonergan said in response to the comments. \u201cAt a time when families and communities across the country are suffering, people are coming together to fight the coronavirus. This Democrat congressman\u2019s threats need and deserve to be condemned.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Creitz |first1=Charles |title=Democratic rep jokes about withholding Lysol shipments to Kentucky in swipe at McConnell |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/malinowski-jokes-withholding-lysol-shipments-kentucky-mcconnell |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Fox News |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski added that this was a 'fantasy' of his that is unlikely actually work.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kane |first1=Paul |title=For House incumbents, campaigning during a pandemic means providing help |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/for-house-incumbents-campaigning-in-the-time-of-a-pandemic-means-providing-help/2020/04/11/baa8695e-7c12-11ea-b6ff-597f170df8f8_story.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=The Washington Post |date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Undocumented Immigrants===\nAt an August 2019 town hall, Malinowski told constituents that undocumented immigrants are needed to mow \"our beautiful lawns\" and perform menial jobs rejected by tech-focused teenagers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ferrechio |first1=Susan |title=Democratic lawmaker: Illegal immigrants needed to mow 'our beautiful lawns' |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/congress/democratic-lawmaker-illegal-immigrants-needed-to-mow-our-beautiful-lawns |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Washington Examiner |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wulfsohn |first1=Joseph |title=Dem Rep. Tom Malinowski: We need illegal immigrants to 'mow our beautiful lawns' |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/dem-rep-tom-malinowski-illegal-immigrants-to-mow-lawns |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Fox News |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref> The comments made national headlines and drew backlash from critics who called Malinowski \"out of touch\". Questions were raised as to whether Malinowski pays undocumented immigrants to mow his personal lawn.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moritz-Rabson |first1=Daniel |title=DEMOCRATIC CONGRESSMAN SAYS UNDOCUMENTED IMMIGRANTS ARE GOOD FOR 'MOWING OUR BEAUTIFUL LAWNS' |url=https://www.newsweek.com/democratic-congressman-says-undocumented-immigrants-are-good-mowing-our-beautiful-lawns-1455893 |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Newsweek |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Prince |first1=Molly |title=WATCH: Dem Lawmaker Says Illegal Immigrants Are Needed To Mow \u2018Our Beautiful Lawns\u2019 |url=https://www.dailywire.com/news/watch-dem-lawmaker-says-illegal-immigrants-are-molly-prince |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=The Daily Wire |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Meads |first1=Timothy |title=WATCH: Dem Lawmaker Says Illegal Immigrants Are Needed To Mow \u2018Our Beautiful Lawns\u2019 |url=New Jersey Democrat: We Need Illegals To Mow Our 'Beautiful Lawns'e |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Townhall |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMalinowski owns a home in [[Washington, D.C.]], and was registered to vote there as of March 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pizarro |first1=Max |title=Residency Question Hounds Malinowski on Eve of Union County Vote |url=https://www.insidernj.com/residency-question-hounds-malinowski-eve-union-county-vote/ |accessdate=16 July 2018 |publisher=InsiderNJ |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref> He began renting a home in [[Rocky Hill, New Jersey]], in September 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brodesser-Akner |first1=Claude |title=What's really going on with all these 'carpetbagger' political attacks in New Jersey? |url=https://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/07/hed_whats_really_going_on_with_all_these_carpetbag.html |accessdate=17 July 2018 |publisher=NJ.com |date=July 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pathe |first1=Simone |title=Could Past DC Residency Be Liability for Some Democrats? |url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/past-dc-residency-liability-democrats |accessdate=16 July 2018 |publisher=Roll Call |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski's stepfather [[Blair Clark]] was a journalist. Clark's sister was [[Anne Clark Martindell|Anne Martindell]], a member of the [[New Jersey State Senate]] (1974\u20131977) and a [[List of ambassadors of the United States to New Zealand|United States ambassador to New Zealand]] (1979\u20131981).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wildstein |first1=David |title=Malinowski and the residency thing |url=https://newjerseyglobe.com/section-2/malinowski-residency-thing/ |accessdate= August 8, 2018 |publisher=New Jersey Globe |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski has one daughter, Emily.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Muscavage |first1=Nick |title= NJ elections: Democrat Tom Malinowski unseats Republican Leonard Lance in NJ's 7th Congressional District  |url=https://www.mycentraljersey.com/story/news/politics/2018/11/07/nj-7th-district-congress-tom-malinowski-defeats-leonard-lance/1902521002/ |accessdate= March 3, 2020 |publisher= Courier News and Home News Tribune |date=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://malinowski.house.gov/ Congressman Tom Malinowski] official U.S. House website\n*[https://malinowskifornj.com/ Tom Malinowski for Congress]\n{{CongLinks|fec=H8NJ07223|votesmart=179645|congbio=M001203|congress=tom-malinowski/M001203}}\n\n{{Commons category|Tomasz P. Malinowski}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Posner (lawyer)|Michael Posner]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Virginia L. Bennett]]<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Leonard Lance]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from New Jersey|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Elaine Luria]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=383rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ben McAdams]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Members of the U.S. House of Representatives}}\n{{NJ-FedRep}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malinowski, Tom}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Antony's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Human Rights Watch people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Princeton, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Rocky Hill, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from S\u0142upsk]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Princeton High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Assistant Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:United States National Security Council staffers]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Progressivism in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Tom Malinowski\n| image               = Tom Malinowski, official portrait, 116th congress.jpg\n| state               = [[New Jersey]]\n| district            = {{ushr|NJ|7|7th}}\n| term_start          = January 3, 2019\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Leonard Lance]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]\n| president1          = [[Barack Obama]]\n| deputy1             = [[Virginia L. Bennett]]\n| term_start1         = April 3, 2014\n| term_end1           = January 20, 2017\n| predecessor1        = [[Michael Posner (lawyer)|Michael Posner]]\n| successor1          = [[Robert Destro]]\n| birth_date          = {{nowrap|{{birth date and age|1965|9|23}}}}\n| birth_place         = [[S\u0142upsk]], [[Poland]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| education           = [[University of California, Berkeley]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[St Antony's College, Oxford]] ([[Master of Philosophy|MPhil]])\n| website             = {{url|malinowski.house.gov|House website}}\n| birth_name          = Tomasz P. Malinowski\n}}\n'''Tomasz P. Malinowski''' (born September 23, 1965)<ref name=\"AllGov\"/> is an  [[United States|American]] politician and diplomat who is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]]. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he previously served as [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]] in the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]]. Malinowski was first elected in [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections|2018]], defeating [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] incumbent [[Leonard Lance]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski Declares|url=https://www.insidernj.com/press-release/tom-malinowski-declares-candidacy-7th-congressional-district/|publisher=InsiderNJ|date=October 2, 2017|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New Jersey Primary Election Results |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/05/us/elections/results-new-jersey-primary-elections.html |accessdate=8 August 2018 |publisher=New York Times |date=June 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMalinowski was born in [[S\u0142upsk]], Poland, and lived in [[Brwin\u00f3w]] until he left the country at the age of six with his mother, Joanna, who married [[Blair Clark]]. He was raised in [[Princeton, New Jersey]], and graduated from [[Princeton High School (New Jersey)|Princeton High School]] in 1983, where he wrote for the school newspaper ''The Tower'' and was an intern in the office of Senator [[Bill Bradley]].<ref name=\"AllGov\">{{cite web|title=Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor: Who Is Tom Malinowski?|url=http://www.allgov.com/news/appointments-and-resignations/assistant-secretary-of-state-for-democracy-human-rights-and-labor-who-is-tom-malinowski-130721?news=850617|publisher=AllGov|date=July 21, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[political science]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]], in 1987 and a [[Master of Philosophy]] from [[St Antony's College, Oxford]], in 1991, where he was a [[Rhodes Scholar]].<ref name=\"AllGov\"/><ref name=\"State\">{{cite web|title=Tom Malinowski|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/224368.htm|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=April 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nMalinowski began his government career as a special assistant for Senator [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] in 1988. After attending Oxford, Malinowski worked for the [[Institute for Human Sciences]] in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]], and later as a research assistant for the [[Ford Foundation]] in 1993.<ref name=\"State\"/> From 1994 to 1998, Malinowski was a speechwriter for secretaries of state [[Warren Christopher]] and [[Madeleine Albright]], as well as a member of the [[Policy Planning Staff (United States)|Policy Planning Staff]] at the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]].<ref name=\"OpenSecrets\"/> From 1998 to 2001, Malinowski served as senior director on the [[United States National Security Council|National Security Council]] at the [[White House]], where he oversaw the drafting of President [[Bill Clinton]]'s foreign policy speeches and [[strategic communications]] efforts around the world.<ref name=\"State\"/><ref name=\"OpenSecrets\"/>\n\n==Human Rights Watch==\nFrom 2001 to 2013, Malinowski was a lobbyist for [[Human Rights Watch]].<ref name=\"State\"/><ref name=\"OpenSecrets\">{{cite web|title=Malinowski, Tom|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/revolving/rev_summary.php?id=78011|publisher=[[Center for Responsive Politics]]|date=April 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=twsPolitico0099/> In this position, he advocated for terrorists' rights during the [[War on Terror]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scher |first1=Brent |title=NJ Dem Tom Malinowski Tries and Fails to Defend Record of \u2018Lobbying for Terrorist Rights\u2019|url=https://freebeacon.com/politics/nj-dem-tom-malinowski-tries-fails-to-defend-record-of-lobbying-for-terrorist-rights/|publisher=[[The Washington Free Beacon]]|date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> Going as far as to say that [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay]] should be shut down.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Malinowski |first1=Tom |title=Four Good Reasons Why Guantanamo Should Be Closed|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2006/11/22/four-good-reasons-why-guantanamo-should-be-closed# |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=November 22, 2006}}</ref> Malinowski also campaigned against American support of the Israeli military. Malinowski opposed the United States supplying the Israeli Defense Forces with cluster munitions and asked then-Senator [[Hillary Clinton]] to not support Israel\u2019s construction of an \u2018illegal\u2019 wall in the West Bank.<ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |title=Human Rights Watch Lobbying Activity|url=https://freebeacon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Screen-Shot-2018-07-20-at-3.00.16-PM.png |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Malinowski |first1=Tom |title=Human Rights watch Lobbying Activity|url=https://freebeacon.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Screen-Shot-2018-07-20-at-3.04.26-PM.png |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\n== Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor ==\nMalinowski was seen by some<ref name=\"Wapo3\">{{cite web|title=Nonprofit Groups Seeking Exceptions to Lobby Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/21/us/politics/21lobby.html|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=April 20, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Wapo4\">{{cite web|title=The Good Lobbyist|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/23/opinion/23thu3.html?mcubz=2|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=April 22, 2006}}</ref> as a likely nominee for [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]] but his previous registration as a lobbyist while at Human Rights Watch necessitated a waiver from the President. On July 8, 2013, during President Obama's second term, Malinowski was nominated to serve as [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]].<ref>{{cite web|title=President Obama Announces More Key Administration Posts|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/07/08/president-obama-announces-more-key-administration-posts|publisher=[[White House]]|date=July 8, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=White House hires lobbyist Malinowski|last=Heil|first=Emily|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/in-the-loop/post/white-house-taps-tom-malinowski-for-human-rights-post/2013/07/09/1395416e-e8a3-11e2-a301-ea5a8116d211_blog.html|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=July 9, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski testified before the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]] on September 24, 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement for the Record by Tom Malinowski, Nominee for Assistant Secretary of State|url=http://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Malinowski.pdf|publisher=[[United States Senate]]|date=September 24, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> and was confirmed by the [[U.S. Senate]] on April 2, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senate confirms State Dept. nominee|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/04/09/senate-confirms-state-dept-nominee/|work=[[Washington Blade]]|date=April 9, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Senate Confirms Tom Malinowski as New Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor|url=http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/press-release/senate-confirms-tom-malinowski-new-assistant-secretary-state-democracy-human-rights|publisher=[[Human Rights First]]|date=April 2, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski confirmed at DRL|url=http://www.demdigest.net/malinowski-confirmed-drl/|publisher=Democracy Digest|date=April 4, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> According to columnist [[Jennifer Rubin (journalist)|Jennifer Rubin]], Malinowski was praised in 2014 by leaders from both parties for his defense of human rights and his work toward ending torture.<ref name=twsWashPost040>Washington Post, Jennifer Rubin, February 21, 2014, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/right-turn/wp/2014/02/21/free-tom-malinowksi/ Free Tom Malinowski], Retrieved May 23, 2018, \"...Tom is widely respected for the indispensable role he has played in defense of human rights and fundamental freedoms, from ending torture to advancing democracy ... He received wide support from Democrats and Republicans who have been united in their criticism of the administration\u2019s ... attitude toward human rights....</ref>\n\nWhile working in the State Department, Malinowski spearheaded efforts to assist persecuted religious minorities targeted by [[ISIS]] in [[Iraq]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A/S Malinowski Briefs Congressional Leaders on ISIL\u2019s Persecution of Religious Minorities in Iraq and Syria=|url=https://geneva.usmission.gov/2014/09/12/as-malinowski-briefs-congressional-leaders-on-isils-persecution-of-religious-minorities-in-iraq-and-syria/|publisher=United States of America Geneva Mission|date=September 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Malinowski Testimony|url=https://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Malinowski_Testimony.pdf|publisher=[[U.S. Senate]]|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> He also oversaw efforts to sanction [[North Korea]]n officials for human rights abuses and increase the flow of uncensored information into the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. compiling list of North Korea human rights violators|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2016/04/27/US-compiling-list-of-North-Korea-human-rights-violators/8071461768502/|publisher=[[UPI]]|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanctions on N.K. leader 'just the start,' more blacklisting to come: senior U.S. diplomat|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2016/07/08/0401000000AEN20160708001200315.html| publisher=[[Yonhap]]|date=July 8, 2016}}</ref> He led State Department efforts to defend the [[LGBT]] community around the world and oversaw the appointment of the first [[Randy W. Berry|Special Envoy for LGBT rights]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Support for Gay Rights in Africa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/29/opinion/support-for-gay-rights-in-africa.html?mcubz=1&mtrref=undefined&assetType=opinion|publisher=|date=December 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Special Envoy for LGBT Rights|url=http://www.hrc.org/blog/welcome-to-the-special-envoy-for-lgbt-rights|publisher=[[Human Rights Campaign]]|date=February 27, 2015}}</ref> Malinowski backed [[United Nations]]' efforts to investigate possible [[Alleged war crimes during the final stages of the Sri Lankan Civil War|war crimes]] committed during the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. to Support Sri Lanka Plan to Investigate War Crimes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/27/world/asia/united-states-supports-sri-lanka-investigation-of-war-crimes.html?mtrref=undefined|publisher=[[NY Times]]|date=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He also worked on decreasing civilian casualties from US military operations in the [[Middle East]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Obama\u2019s New Executive Order Increases Drone Transparency, Official Says|url=https://www.washingtonreport.me/2016-august/september/obamas-new-executive-order-increases-drone-transparency-official-says.html|publisher=[[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]]|date=August 2016}}</ref> and assisted with sanctioning Russian officials for [[Magnitsky Act|human rights abuses]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Five Russians blacklisted for alleged human rights abuses|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/five-russians-blacklisted-for-human-rights-abuses/2017/01/09/1b00068c-d6b6-11e6-9f9f-5cdb4b7f8dd7_story.html|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=January 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Malinowski and Omar in 2019.png|thumb|Malinowski with [[Ilhan Omar]] in [[Washington DC]], 2019]]\nIn July 2014, Malinowski was [[persona non grata|expelled]] by [[Bahrain]]'s [[Government of Bahrain|government]] after meeting with members of an opposition group in the course of a scheduled visit.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|title=US diplomat Tom Malinowski expelled from Bahrain|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-28204511|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bahrain: U.S. diplomat 'unwelcome and should immediately leave'|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/07/08/world/meast/bahrain-us-diplomat-unwelcome/|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=July 8, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bahrain expels top US diplomat after meeting with main opposition group|url=https://www.rt.com/news/171084-bahrain-expels-us-diplomat/|publisher=[[RT (TV network)|RT]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> The foreign ministry of Bahrain argued that Malinowski's meeting improperly intervened in the country's affairs but noted the incident would not affect [[Bahrain\u2013United States relations]].<ref name=\"BBC\"/> The [[U.S. State Department]] released a statement of concern about the actions while [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]] called Bahrain's actions unacceptable and contrary to diplomatic protocol.<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite web|last=Schwartz|first=Felicia|title=Tension Between Bahrain and U.S. Continues Over Diplomat's Expulsion|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tension-between-bahrain-and-u-s-continues-over-diplomats-expulsion-1405387624|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=July 14, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Statement on the Decision by the Government of Bahrain To Find Assistant Secretary Malinowski Persona Non Grata and To Expel Him From Bahrain|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2014/07/228839.htm|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Malinowski returned to the country in December 2014 with the [[Anne W. Patterson|assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern affairs]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gordon|first=Michael|title=Expelled U.S. Official to Return to Bahrain|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/03/world/middleeast/bahrain-us-human-rights-official-tom-malinowski.html?_r=0|work=[[New York Times]]|date=December 3, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Press Availability with A/S Tom Malinowski and A/S Anne Patterson|url=http://bahrain.usembassy.gov/pas-120414.html|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=December 4, 2014|accessdate=April 1, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414204305/http://bahrain.usembassy.gov/pas-120414.html|archivedate=April 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the end of his tenure at the State Department, Malinowski joined fellow former Obama officials to lobby Congress in an effort to prevent the [[Trump Administration]] from lifting the [[International sanctions during the Ukrainian crisis|sanctions]] on [[Russia]] following its [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|invasion of Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Diplomats: Trump Team Sought to Lift Sanctions on Russia|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/former-diplomats-trump-team-sought-lift-sanctions-russia-n767406|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=June 1, 2017}}</ref> He criticized [[Donald Trump]] for having an \"obscene fondness\" for the world's tyrants and for instituting a \"complete departure from decades of American tradition.\"<ref name=twsPolitico0099>Politico magazine, Susan B. Glasser, June 19, 2017, [https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/06/19/tom-malinowski-man-who-argued-with-dictators-215278 The Man Who Argued With Dictators: Tom Malinowski spent years trying to get President Obama to care more about human rights. Now, he\u2019s figuring out what to do with a president who doesn\u2019t seem to care at all.], Retrieved May 24, 2018, \"...Malinowski spent the past few years pushing Obama from the inside on human rights ... former Washington director of Human Rights Watch ... leading the resistance from the outside to Trump and what he calls his \u201cobscene\u201d fondness for the world\u2019s tyrants....\"</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\nOn October 2, 2017, Malinowski announced his candidacy for U.S. Congress in [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]] in the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kamisar|first1=Ben|title=Obama State Department official to run for House in NJ|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/353408-obama-state-department-official-to-run-for-house-in-nj|accessdate=16 May 2018|publisher=The Hill|date=October 2, 2017}}</ref> He decided to run for Congress after the [[2016 United States presidential election|November 2016 election of Donald Trump]], which he saw as an indication that America was in \"deep trouble.\"<ref name=twsBloomberg445>Albert R. Hunt, May 2, 2018, Bloomberg News, [https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-05-02/democratic-house-candidates-look-mighty-familiar Some Democratic Candidates Look Mighty Familiar], Retrieved May 15, 2018, \"... Malinowski, an assistant secretary of State for President Obama and a State Department official under Clinton ... America, he believes, \"is in deep trouble.\"...\"</ref> Malinowski said he decided to run for office because of what he called the Trump administration's \"effort to take down the Affordable Care Act with no viable replacement. It was the Muslim ban, and attacks on immigrants, it was the tearing up of alliances and commitments internationally. It was the taking down of environmental protections, it was refusing to invest in infrastructure.\"<ref name=\"twsNBCWash11\">May 27, 2018, NBC News Washington (Channel 4), [https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/politics/Former-Obama-Staffers-Elections-483805841.html Fired Up by Trump, Dozens of Former Obama Staffers Run for Office: The surge of Democratic candidates with ties to Obama has the potential to fill state and federal legislatures with like-minded allies], Retrieved May 30, 2018, \"...it was the effort to take down the Affordable Care Act with no viable replacement...\"</ref>\n\nMalinowski supports the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] and criticized the Republican Party for \"whittling away at the Affordable Care Act year after year.\"<ref name=twsInsiderNJ44>Insider New Jersey, May 12, 2018, Staff writer, [https://www.insidernj.com/cd7-democratic-challenger-malinowski-formally-opens-main-headquarters-pallone/ CD7 Democratic Challenger Malinowski Formally Opens his Main Headquarters with Pallone], Retrieved May 14, 2018, \"... He\u2019ll fight to protect the Affordable Care Act.....\"</ref>  He supports raising the minimum wage to $15 per hour as well as enhanced collective bargaining rights and protections for workers.<ref name=twsNJGlobe11/>  Malinowski sees the Democratic Party, in contrast to the GOP, as promoting fiscal responsibility, law enforcement, family values, and patriotism.<ref name=\"twsWashPost0786\">E. J. Dionne, July 15, 2018, Washington Post, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/does-the-blue-wave-start-in-jersey/2018/07/15/db44a0b2-86e4-11e8-8f6c-46cb43e3f306_story.html?wpisrc=nl_headlines&wpmm=1 Does the blue wave start in Jersey?], Retrieved July 16, 2018</ref>\n\n[[File:Candidate for Congress NJ-7th Tom Malinowski at campaign headquarters speaking with a voter.jpg|thumb|upright|Malinowski at his campaign headquarters in [[Martinsville, New Jersey]]]]\nHis endorsements included the Hunterdon County Democratic Committee<ref name=\"twsNJHills41\">April 27, 2018, New Jersey Hills, [http://www.newjerseyhills.com/hunterdon_review/news/first-lady-tammy-murphy-to-speak-at-county-democratic-brunch/article_a25ed6e9-39ca-56e0-a286-f38ca8e86f59.html First Lady Tammy Murphy to speak at county Democratic brunch on Sunday, April 29], Retrieved May 15, 2018, \"...Tom Malinowski ... endorsed by the HCDC ...\"</ref> and the [[Communications Workers of America]].<ref name=\"twsNJGlobe11\">David Wildstein, April 23, 2018, New Jersey Globe, [https://newjerseyglobe.com/congress/cwa-endorses-malinowski/ CWA Endorses Malinowski], Retrieved May 15, 2018</ref> On June 5, 2018, he faced social worker Peter Jacob and lawyer Goutam Jois.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Jersey's 7th Congressional District election, 2018|url=https://ballotpedia.org/New_Jersey%27s_7th_Congressional_District_election,_2018|accessdate=8 May 2018|publisher=Ballotpedia}}</ref> He defeated Jacob and Jois, receiving 66.8% of the vote and winning all counties in the district<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-jersey-house-district-7-primary-election|title=New Jersey Primary Election Results: Seventh House District|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njelections.org/assets/pdf/election-results/2018/2018-official-primary-results-us-house.pdf|title=Candidates for House of Representatives For PRIMARY ELECTION 06/05/2018 Election,|last=|first=|date=July 20, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Malinowski went onto to defeat incumbent Republican [[Leonard Lance]].\n\nMalinowski criticized Lance, saying he \"shifted to the right when he was scared of the [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] and he's moving to the left when he's scared of his increasingly moderate and energized constituents.\"<ref name=\"twsNJcom441\">Jonathan D. Salant, May 14, 2018, NJ.com, [http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/05/how_njs_most_endangered_congressman_is_trying_to_w.html This N.J. Republican is in big trouble because of Trump. Here's what he's doing about it.], Retrieved May 15, 2018</ref> On November 6, Malinowski won the election, receiving 51.7% of the vote. While Malinowski and Lance each carried three of the six counties in the district, Malinowski won the district's shares of Somerset and Union counties by a combined 22,300 votes, more than the overall margin of 16,200 votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-jersey-house-district-7|title=New Jersey\u2019s Seventh House District Election Results: Tom Malinowski vs. Leonard Lance|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njelections.org/assets/pdf/election-results/2018/2018-official-general-election-results-us-house.pdf|title=Official List Candidates for House of Representatives For GENERAL ELECTION 11/06/2018 Election|last=|first=|date=December 3, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> When he took office in January 2019, he became the first Democrat to represent the 7th and its predecessors since 1961.\n\nOn February 26, 2020, Malinowski stated that he would \u201cabsolutely\u201d support [[Bernie Sanders]] if he were the Democratic Presidential nominee.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mascaro |first1=Lisa |title=Pelosi urges Democratic unity amid Sanders\u2019 campaign surge |url=https://apnews.com/7ef003d3d777ba44bb4e24fed66809f8 |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=The Associated Press |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n\n* [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|'''Committee on Foreign Affairs''']]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism|Subcommittee on the Middle East, North Africa and International Terrorism]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|'''Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure''']]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n\n=== Caucus memberships ===\n* '''[[LGBT Equality Caucus]]'''\n* '''[[New Democrat Coalition]]'''\n* '''End Corruption Caucus'''<ref name=\"Malinowski Press Release 2020.01.21\">{{cite web |title=Representative Malinowski Leads Fight To End Corruption in Washington |url=https://malinowski.house.gov/media/press-releases/representative-malinowski-leads-fight-end-corruption-washington |website=Tom Malinowski Congressional Web Site |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Congressman Max Rose Press Release 2020.01.16\">{{cite web |title=10 Years After Disastrous Citizens United Decision, Rose, Porter, Freshmen Dems Launch New \u2018End Corruption\u2019 Caucus |url=https://maxrose.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=2450 |website=Max Rose Congressional Web Site |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===COVID-19===\nMalinowski joked during an April 2020 livestream with constituents that he would withhold shipments of [[Lysol]] disinfectant to the state of [[Kentucky]] until [[Senate Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]], relents in his opposition to Democrat-backed vote-by-mail measures amid the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]]. He was referring to a [[Reckitt Benckiser]] manufacturing plant located in [[Hillsborough Township, New Jersey|Hillsborough Township]] which produces 100% of the United States' supply of Lysol disinfectant.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Snowflack |first1=Fred |title=Kentucky Strikes Back at Malinowski |url=https://www.insidernj.com/kentucky-strikes-back-at-malinowski/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Insider NJ |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Saxena |first1=Vivek |title=\u2018We make 100 percent\u2019: NJ Dem \u2018jokes\u2019 about withholding Lysol products to strongarm Mitch McConnell |url=https://www.bizpacreview.com/2020/04/10/we-make-100-percent-nj-dem-jokes-about-withholding-lysol-products-to-strongarm-mitch-mcconnell-906928 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Biz Pac Review |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"There\u2019s nothing funny about a member of Congress threatening to withhold vital supplies from Kentuckians during a deadly outbreak,\u201d [[Republican Party of Kentucky]] spokesman Mike Lonergan said in response to the comments. \u201cAt a time when families and communities across the country are suffering, people are coming together to fight the coronavirus. This Democrat congressman\u2019s threats need and deserve to be condemned.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Creitz |first1=Charles |title=Democratic rep jokes about withholding Lysol shipments to Kentucky in swipe at McConnell |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/malinowski-jokes-withholding-lysol-shipments-kentucky-mcconnell |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Fox News |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski added that this was a 'fantasy' of his that is unlikely actually work.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kane |first1=Paul |title=For House incumbents, campaigning during a pandemic means providing help |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/for-house-incumbents-campaigning-in-the-time-of-a-pandemic-means-providing-help/2020/04/11/baa8695e-7c12-11ea-b6ff-597f170df8f8_story.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=The Washington Post |date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Illegal Immigrants===\nAt an August 2019 town hall, Malinowski told constituents that illegal immigrants are needed to mow \"our beautiful lawns\" and perform menial jobs rejected by tech-focused teenagers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ferrechio |first1=Susan |title=Democratic lawmaker: Illegal immigrants needed to mow 'our beautiful lawns' |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/congress/democratic-lawmaker-illegal-immigrants-needed-to-mow-our-beautiful-lawns |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Washington Examiner |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wulfsohn |first1=Joseph |title=Dem Rep. Tom Malinowski: We need illegal immigrants to 'mow our beautiful lawns' |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/dem-rep-tom-malinowski-illegal-immigrants-to-mow-lawns |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Fox News |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref> The comments made national headlines and drew backlash from critics who called Malinowski \"out of touch\". Questions were raised as to whether Malinowski pays illegal immigrants to mow his personal lawn.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moritz-Rabson |first1=Daniel |title=DEMOCRATIC CONGRESSMAN SAYS UNDOCUMENTED IMMIGRANTS ARE GOOD FOR 'MOWING OUR BEAUTIFUL LAWNS' |url=https://www.newsweek.com/democratic-congressman-says-undocumented-immigrants-are-good-mowing-our-beautiful-lawns-1455893 |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Newsweek |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Prince |first1=Molly |title=WATCH: Dem Lawmaker Says Illegal Immigrants Are Needed To Mow \u2018Our Beautiful Lawns\u2019 |url=https://www.dailywire.com/news/watch-dem-lawmaker-says-illegal-immigrants-are-molly-prince |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=The Daily Wire |date=August 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Meads |first1=Timothy |title=WATCH: Dem Lawmaker Says Illegal Immigrants Are Needed To Mow \u2018Our Beautiful Lawns\u2019 |url=New Jersey Democrat: We Need Illegals To Mow Our 'Beautiful Lawns'e |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Townhall |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Impeachment===\nMalinowski was the first member of the New Jersey congressional delegation to call to begin the impeachment inquiry of President [[Donald Trump]] in May 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moran |first1=Tom |title=Malinowski, the first Jersey House member to favor impeachment hearings, explains why|url=https://www.nj.com/opinion/2019/05/malinowski-the-first-jersey-house-member-to-favor-impeachment-hearings-explains-why-moran.html |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=NJ.com |date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> At the time, he was the only swing-district Democrat to support opening an impeachment inquiry into the President. Malinowski came under sharp criticism from constituents at subsequent town hall meetings as well as in press.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff |first1=The |title=Malinowski discovers vocal impeachment opposition at Branchburg town hall |url=https://savejersey.com/2019/12/malinowski-discovers-vocal-impeachment-opposition-at-branchburg-town-hall/ |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=Save Jersey |date=December 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Parker-Maygar |first1=Alex |title=Malinowski talks impeachment at town hall as House vote looms |url=https://www.newjerseyhills.com/videos-malinowski-talks-impeachment-at-town-hall-as-house-vote/article_c3f3ed11-b7ff-5300-b051-24899abb62f2.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=New Jersey Globe |date=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMalinowski owns a home in [[Washington, D.C.]], and was registered to vote there as of March 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pizarro |first1=Max |title=Residency Question Hounds Malinowski on Eve of Union County Vote |url=https://www.insidernj.com/residency-question-hounds-malinowski-eve-union-county-vote/ |accessdate=16 July 2018 |publisher=InsiderNJ |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref> He began renting a home in [[Rocky Hill, New Jersey]], in September 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brodesser-Akner |first1=Claude |title=What's really going on with all these 'carpetbagger' political attacks in New Jersey? |url=https://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/07/hed_whats_really_going_on_with_all_these_carpetbag.html |accessdate=17 July 2018 |publisher=NJ.com |date=July 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pathe |first1=Simone |title=Could Past DC Residency Be Liability for Some Democrats? |url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/past-dc-residency-liability-democrats |accessdate=16 July 2018 |publisher=Roll Call |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski's stepfather [[Blair Clark]] was a journalist. Clark's sister was [[Anne Clark Martindell|Anne Martindell]], a member of the [[New Jersey State Senate]] (1974\u20131977) and a [[List of ambassadors of the United States to New Zealand|United States ambassador to New Zealand]] (1979\u20131981).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wildstein |first1=David |title=Malinowski and the residency thing |url=https://newjerseyglobe.com/section-2/malinowski-residency-thing/ |accessdate= August 8, 2018 |publisher=New Jersey Globe |date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMalinowski has one daughter, Emily.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Muscavage |first1=Nick |title= NJ elections: Democrat Tom Malinowski unseats Republican Leonard Lance in NJ's 7th Congressional District  |url=https://www.mycentraljersey.com/story/news/politics/2018/11/07/nj-7th-district-congress-tom-malinowski-defeats-leonard-lance/1902521002/ |accessdate= March 3, 2020 |publisher= Courier News and Home News Tribune |date=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://malinowski.house.gov/ Congressman Tom Malinowski] official U.S. House website\n*[https://malinowskifornj.com/ Tom Malinowski for Congress]\n{{CongLinks|fec=H8NJ07223|votesmart=179645|congbio=M001203|congress=tom-malinowski/M001203}}\n\n{{Commons category|Tomasz P. Malinowski}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Posner (lawyer)|Michael Posner]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Virginia L. Bennett]]<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Leonard Lance]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from New Jersey|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[New Jersey's 7th congressional district]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Elaine Luria]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=383rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ben McAdams]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Members of the U.S. House of Representatives}}\n{{NJ-FedRep}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malinowski, Tom}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Antony's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Human Rights Watch people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Princeton, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Rocky Hill, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from S\u0142upsk]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Princeton High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Assistant Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:United States National Security Council staffers]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Progressivism in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Amishai GG", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Name fix)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Malinowski"}
{"title_page": "IPhone (1st generation)", "text_new": "{{lower case}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox mobile phone\n| name = iPhone\n| logo = IPhonelogo.svg\n| logosize = 200px\n| image =iPhone 1st Gen.svg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| caption =\n| developer = [[Apple Inc.]]\n| manufacturer = [[Foxconn]] ([[contract manufacturer]])<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/iphone-manufacturer-to-pay-family-of-dead-worker/ \n |title=iPhone manufacturer to pay family of dead worker \n |first=Jim \n |last=Dalrymple \n |date=July 28, 2018\n |publisher=[[CNET]] \n |access-date=March 31, 2020\n}}</ref>{{verify source|date=March 2018}}\n| slogan = {{plainlist|\n*\"This is only the beginning.\"\n*\"Apple reinvents the phone.\"}}\n| form         = [[mobile phone form factors#Touchscreen.2FSlate|Slate]]\n| serieslabel  = [[History of iPhone|Generation]] \n| series       = 1st\n| modelnumber  = A1203<ref>{{cite web|title=Identify your iPhone model |url=http://support.apple.com/kb/HT3939 |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924093929/http://support.apple.com/kb/HT3939 |archivedate=September 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n| type         = [[Smartphone]]\n| releasedate  = {{start date and age|2007|6|29}}\n| discontinued = {{end date and age|2008|7|15}}\n| price = $499&nbsp;4&nbsp;[[gigabyte|GB]], $599&nbsp;8&nbsp;GB\n| unitssold = 6.1 million\n| media =\n| os = {{plainlist|\n*'''Original:''' [[iPhone OS 1|iPhone OS 1.0]]\n*'''Last:''' [[iPhone OS 3|iPhone OS 3.1.3]]\n*Released {{start date and age|2010|02|02}}}}\n| input = {{plainlist|\n*[[Multi-touch]] [[touchscreen]] display\n*3-axis [[accelerometer]]\n*[[Proximity sensor]]\n*[[photodetector|Ambient light sensor]]\n*[[Microphone]]\n*[[iPhone#Audio and output|Headset controls]]}}\n| camera = 2.0&nbsp;[[megapixel|MP]] with [[geotagging]] (Not [[Global Positioning System|GPS]]-based)\n| battery = 3.7&nbsp;[[Volt|V]] 1400&nbsp;[[Ampere-hour|mAh]] [[Lithium-ion battery]]<ref name=battery_specs>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.ipodbatteryfaq.com/ipodbatteryandpower.html\n |title       = iPod and iPhone Battery and Power Specifications\n |publisher   = iPodBatteryFAQ.com\n |accessdate  = May 12, 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090207054030/http://www.ipodbatteryfaq.com/ipodbatteryandpower.html\n |archivedate = February 7, 2009\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n| cpu = [[Samsung]] [[32-bit]] [[reduced instruction set computer|RISC]] [[ARM architecture|ARM]] 1176JZ(F)-S v1.0<ref name=\"Processor\">{{cite web\n |url=http://toucharcade.com/2008/07/07/under-the-hood-the-iphones-gaming-mettle/ \n |title=Under the Hood: The iPhone\u2019s Gaming Mettle \n |last=Patterson \n |first=Blake \n |date=July 7, 2008 \n |publisher=touchArcade \n |accessdate=March 20, 2009 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307192637/http://toucharcade.com/2008/07/07/under-the-hood-the-iphones-gaming-mettle/ \n |archivedate=March 7, 2009 \n}}</ref> 620&nbsp;[[Hertz|MHz]]<br>[[underclocking|Underclocked]] to 412&nbsp;MHz<ref>{{cite web \n |url=http://www.roughlydrafted.com/2008/03/20/iphone-20-sdk-video-games-to-rival-nintendo-ds-sony-psp/ \n |title=iPhone 2.0 SDK: Video Games to Rival Nintendo DS, Sony PSP \n |last=Dilger \n |first=Daniel Eran \n |date=March 20, 2008 \n |publisher=RoughlyDrafted Magazine \n |accessdate=May 12, 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090516183456/http://www.roughlydrafted.com/2008/03/20/iphone-20-sdk-video-games-to-rival-nintendo-ds-sony-psp/ \n |archivedate=May 16, 2009 \n }}</ref>\n | gpu = [[PowerVR]] [[PowerVR#MBX|MBX]] Lite 3D [[graphics processing unit|GPU]]<ref>{{cite web \n |url=https://www.eetimes.com/iphone-code-trail-points-to-mbx-graphics-core/ \n |title=IPhone code trail points to MBX graphics core \n |first=Peter \n |last=Clarke \n |date=July 6, 2007 \n |website=[[EE Times]] \n |access-date=March 31, 2020\n }}</ref>\n| storage = 4, 8, or 16&nbsp;[[gigabyte|GB]] [[flash memory]]\n| memory = 128&nbsp;[[megabyte|MB]] [[eDRAM]]<ref name=\"DRAM\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.ubmtechinsights.com/reports-and-subscriptions/device-library/Device-Profile/?SINumber=18016 \n |title=Apple (Samsung S5L8900) applications processor with eDRAM \n |publisher=SUBM TechInsights \n |accessdate=May 12, 2009 \n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715023945/http://www.ubmtechinsights.com/reports-and-subscriptions/device-library/Device-Profile/?SINumber=18016 \n |archivedate=July 15, 2010 \n}}</ref>\n| display = {{plainlist|\n* 90mm (3.5\") screen (diagonally)\n*320\u00d7480&nbsp;[[pixel]] [[image resolution|resolution]] at 163&nbsp;[[pixel density|ppi]]\n*2:3 [[Display aspect ratio|aspect ratio]]\n*18-bit (262,144-color) [[liquid crystal display|LCD]]}}\n| sound = {{plainlist|\n*Single [[loudspeaker]]\n*[[TRS connector#Aircraft headsets|TRRS headphone jack]], 20&nbsp;Hz to 20&nbsp;kHz [[frequency response]] (internal, headset)\n*[[Microphone]]}}\n| connectivity = {{plainlist|\n*[[Quad-band]] [[GSM]]/[[General Packet Radio Service|GPRS]]/[[Enhanced Data Rates for GSM Evolution|EDGE]]<br>([[GSM frequency bands|850, 900, 1800, 1900]]&nbsp;[[Hertz|MHz]])\n*[[Wi-Fi]] ([[IEEE 802.11|802.11]] [[IEEE 802.11b-1999|b]]/[[IEEE 802.11g-2003|g]])\n*[[Bluetooth#Bluetooth v2.0 + EDR|Bluetooth 2.0]]\n*[[Universal Serial Bus|USB 2.0]]/[[Dock connector]]<ref>{{cite web\n | url = https://www.apple.com/iphone/specs.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070714051039/http://www.apple.com/iphone/specs.html\n | archivedate = July 14, 2007\n | title = iPhone&nbsp;\u2013 Tech Specs\n | date = July 14, 2007\n | publisher = Apple\n | accessdate =January 19, 2009}}</ref>}}\n| dimensions = {{plainlist|\n*{{convert|115|mm|in|abbr=on}} H\n*{{convert|61|mm|in|abbr=on}} W\n*{{convert|11.6|mm|in|abbr=on}} D}}\n| weight = {{convert|135|g|oz|abbr=on}}\n| predecessor = [[Apple Newton]]\n| successor = [[iPhone 3G]]\n| related = [[iPad]], [[iPod Touch]] ([[list of iOS devices|comparison]])\n| website = {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629082318/http://www.apple.com:80/iphone/|date=June 29, 2007 |title=Apple - iPhone}}\n}}\n{{iPhone models}}\nThe '''iPhone''' (colloquially known as the '''iPhone 2G''' and '''iPhone 1''' after 2008 to differentiate it from later models) is the first [[smartphone]] designed and marketed by [[Apple Inc.]] After years of rumors and speculation, it was officially announced on January 9, 2007,<ref>{{cite web|author=Dolan, Brian |title=Timeline of Apple \"iPhone\" Rumors (1999\u2013Present) |url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/story/timeline-apple-iphone-rumors-1999-present |accessdate=February 17, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080415055303/http://www.fiercewireless.com/story/timeline-apple-iphone-rumors-1999-present |archivedate=April 15, 2008 }}</ref> and was later released in the United States on June 29, 2007. It featured [[quad-band]] [[GSM]] cellular connectivity with [[GPRS]] and [[Enhanced Data Rates for GSM Evolution|EDGE]] support for data transfer.\n\nDevelopment of the iPhone dated back to 2005, when former Apple CEO [[Steve Jobs]] conceived the idea. The design was expanded upon over the next 2 years in complete secrecy, before being announced in Q1 of 2007.\n\nAlthough several aspects of the iPhone are considered obsolete by current standards, the device is seen as a prototype for current cell phones, eliminating most physical hardware buttons and stylus in favor of a touch-based user interface. Its successor, the [[iPhone 3G]], was announced in June 2008.\n\n==History==\n{{main | History of iPhone}}\nIn 2005, Apple CEO [[Steve Jobs]] conceived an idea of using a [[touchscreen]] to interact with a computer in a way in which he could directly type onto the display, instead of requiring a stylus which was common on existing technology of the time. He decided that the device would require a triple layered [[Capacitive touchscreen|capacitive]] [[multi-touch]] [[touch screen]], a very new and advanced technology at the time. This helped out with removing the physical [[keyboard (computing)|keyboard]] and [[mouse (computing)|mouse]], the same as a [[tablet computer]]. Jobs recruited a group of Apple engineers to investigate the idea as a side project.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cohen |first=Peter |url=http://www.macworld.com/news/2007/01/09/liveupdate/index.php |title=Macworld Expo Keynote Live Update |publisher=[[Macworld]] |date=January 9, 2007 |accessdate=February 1, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070127110536/http://www.macworld.com/news/2007/01/09/liveupdate/index.php |archivedate=January 27, 2007 }}</ref>  When Jobs reviewed the prototype and its [[user interface]], he saw the potential in developing the concept into a mobile phone.<ref>{{cite video\n |people=[[Walter Mossberg]]; [[Kara Swisher]] \n |date=June 2, 2010 \n |title=D8: Steve Jobs on the iPhone's Origin \n |url=http://allthingsd.com/20100601/d8-video-steve-jobs-on-the-origins-of-the-ipad/ \n |publisher=All Things Digital \n |accessdate=June 20, 2010 \n |time=0:20 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525110502/http://allthingsd.com/20100601/d8-video-steve-jobs-on-the-origins-of-the-ipad/ \n |archivedate=May 25, 2011 \n}}</ref> The whole effort was called Project Purple 2 and began in 2005.<ref>{{cite news\n |last=Murtazin \n |first=Eldar \n |url=http://mobile-review.com/articles/2010/iphone-history3-en.shtml \n |title=Apple's Phone: From 1980s' Sketches to iPhone. Part 3 \n |publisher=Mobile-review \n |date=June 20, 2010 \n |accessdate=March 27, 2011 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511134715/http://mobile-review.com/articles/2010/iphone-history3-en.shtml \n |archivedate=May 11, 2011 \n}}</ref>\n\nApple created the device during a secretive and unprecedented collaboration with [[AT&T Mobility|Cingular Wireless]], now part of [[AT&T]]. The development cost of the collaboration was estimated to have been $150 million<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.wired.com/gadgets/wireless/magazine/16-02/ff_iphone \n |title=The Untold Story: How the iPhone Blew Up the Wireless Industry \n |first=Fred \n |last=Vogelstein \n |date=January 9, 2008 \n |work=[[Wired News]] \n |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications]] \n |pages=3\u20134 \n |accessdate=January 10, 2008 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509154531/http://www.wired.com/gadgets/wireless/magazine/16-02/ff_iphone \n |archivedate=May 9, 2008 \n}}</ref> over a thirty-month period. Apple rejected the \"[[design by committee]]\" approach that had yielded the [[Motorola ROKR E1]], a largely unsuccessful collaboration with [[Motorola]]. Instead, Cingular Wireless gave Apple the liberty to develop the iPhone's hardware and software [[in-house]].<ref name=\"CNN secrets\">{{cite news\n |url=http://money.cnn.com/2007/01/10/commentary/lewis_fortune_iphone.fortune/index.htm \n |title=How Apple kept its iPhone secrets \n |last=Lewis \n |first=Peter \n |date=January 12, 2007 \n |publisher=[[CNNMoney.com]] \n |accessdate=January 11, 2009 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210110636/http://money.cnn.com/2007/01/10/commentary/lewis_fortune_iphone.fortune/index.htm \n |archivedate=December 10, 2008 \n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.wired.com/gadgets/wireless/magazine/16-02/ff_iphone \n |title=The Untold Story: How the iPhone Blew Up the Wireless Industry \n |first=Fred \n |last=Vogelstein \n |date=January 9, 2008 \n |work=[[Wired News]] \n |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications \n |pages=1\u20134 \n |accessdate=January 10, 2008 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509154531/http://www.wired.com/gadgets/wireless/magazine/16-02/ff_iphone \n |archivedate=May 9, 2008 \n}}</ref>\nThe original iPhone was introduced by Steve Jobs on January 9, 2007 in a [[Stevenote|keynote address]] at the [[Macworld Conference & Expo#2007|Macworld Conference & Expo]] held in [[Moscone Center|Moscone West]] in San Francisco, California.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.macworld.com/article/54764/2007/01/liveupdate.html \n |title=Macworld Expo Keynote Live Update \n |first=Peter \n |last=Cohen \n |date=March 13, 2007 \n |work=[[Macworld]] \n |accessdate=July 21, 2010 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724170414/http://www.macworld.com/article/54764/2007/01/liveupdate.html \n |archivedate=July 24, 2010 \n}}</ref> In his address, Jobs said, \"This is a day, that I have been looking forward to for two and a half years\", and that \"today, Apple is going to reinvent the phone.\"<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.zdnet.com/blog/btl/jobs-today-apple-is-going-to-reinvent-the-phone/4249 \n |title=Jobs: Today Apple is going to reinvent the phone \n |first=Dan \n |last=Farber \n |date=January 9, 2007 \n |work=[[ZDNet]] \"Between the Lines\" blog \n |accessdate=June 20, 2010 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719225803/http://www.zdnet.com/blog/btl/jobs-today-apple-is-going-to-reinvent-the-phone/4249 \n |archivedate=July 19, 2010 \n}}</ref> Jobs introduced the iPhone as a combination of three devices: a \"widescreen iPod with touch controls\"; a \"revolutionary mobile phone\"; and a \"breakthrough Internet communicator\".<ref>{{cite video\n |people      = Jobs, Steve\n |date        = January 19, 2007\n |url         = https://www.apple.com/quicktime/qtv/mwsf07/\n |title       = Macworld San Francisco 2007 Keynote Address\n |location    = San Francisco\n |publisher   = Apple, Inc.\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20101222223204/http://www.apple.com/quicktime/qtv/mwsf07/\n |archivedate = December 22, 2010\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nSix weeks prior to the iPhone's release, the plastic screen was replaced with glass, after Jobs was upset that the screen of the prototype he was carrying in his pocket had been scratched by his keys. The quick switch led to a bidding process for a manufacturing contractor that was won by [[Foxconn]], which had just opened up a new wing of its [[Shenzhen]] factory complex specifically for this bid.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/22/business/apple-america-and-a-squeezed-middle-class.html|title=Apple, America and a Squeezed Middle Class|last=Duhigg|first=Charles|date=January 21, 2012|work=[[New York Times]]|access-date=September 4, 2018|last2=Bradsher|first2=Keith|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n[[File:First iPhone Macworld 2007 DSCF1286.agr.jpg|thumb|First iPhone on display under glass at 2007 Macworld]]\nThe iPhone was released in the United States on June 29, 2007 at the price of $499 for the 4&nbsp;GB model and $599 for the 8&nbsp;GB model, both requiring a 2-year contract.<ref name=macworldlive>{{cite news\n |last=Cohen\n |first=Peter\n |url=http://www.macworld.com/news/2007/01/09/liveupdate/index.php\n |title=Macworld Expo Keynote Live Update\n |publisher=[[Macworld]]\n |date=January 9, 2007\n |accessdate=February 1, 2007\n |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070127110536/http://www.macworld.com/news/2007/01/09/liveupdate/index.php\n |archivedate=January 27, 2007 }}</ref> Thousands of people were reported to have waited outside [[Apple Store|Apple]] and [[AT&T]] retail stores days before the device's launch;<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://images.apple.com/pr/pdf/q307data_sum.pdf \n |title=Apple Inc. Q3 2007 Unaudited Summary Data \n |accessdate=June 6, 2008 \n |date=July 25, 2007 \n |format=PDF \n |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080529133618/http://images.apple.com/pr/pdf/q307data_sum.pdf \n |archivedate=May 29, 2008 \n}}</ref> many stores reported stock shortages within an hour of availability. To avoid repeating the problems of the [[PlayStation 3 launch]], which caused [[burglary|burglaries]] and even a shooting, off-duty police officers were hired to guard stores overnight.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/29/AR2007062901080.html\n |title=Hype Meets Reality At iPhone's Debut\n |author1=Hart, Kim\n |author2=Valle, Sabrina\n |date=June 30, 2007\n |work=[[The Washington Post]]\n |accessdate=March 3, 2018\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012204641/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/29/AR2007062901080.html\n |archivedate=2008-10-12\n}}</ref><ref name=guardianswarm>{{cite news\n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2007/jun/29/usnews.apple \n |title=iPhone causes big Apple swarm in Big Apple storms \n |first=Bobbie \n |last=Johnson \n |date=June 30, 2007 \n |work=The Guardian \n |accessdate=February 1, 2007 \n |location=London \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130831124543/http://www.theguardian.com/news/2007/jun/29/usnews.apple \n |archivedate=August 31, 2013 \n}}</ref>\n\nIt was later made available in the [[United Kingdom]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Portugal]], the [[Republic of Ireland]], and [[Austria]] in November 2007.<ref name=macworldlive />{{Failed verification|date=January 2019}}\n\nSix out of ten Americans surveyed said they knew the iPhone was coming before its release.<ref name=guardianswarm />\n\n==Post-release==\nThe iPhone's main competitors in both consumer and business markets were considered to be the [[LG Prada]], [[LG Viewty]], [[Samsung Ultra Smart F700]], [[Nokia N95]], [[Nokia E61i]], [[Palm Treo 750]], [[Palm Centro]], [[HTC Touch]], [[Sony Ericsson W960]] and [[BlackBerry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newlaunches.com/archives/top_5_competitors_to_the_iphone.php|title=Top 5 competitors to the iPhone|first=Dhiram|last=Shah|date=February 27, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yugatech.com/mobile/iphone-vs-blackjack-vs-n95-vs-treo-750-vs-bc-8300/|title=iPhone vs. Blackjack vs. N95 vs. Treo 750 vs. BC 8300|first=Abe|last=Olandres|date=June 19, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/6253704.stm|title=Apple iPhone faces serious rivals|first=Rory|last=Cellan-Jones|date=June 29, 2007|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/technology/7081636.stm|title=Who's afraid of the iPhone?|first=Darren|last=Waters|date=November 7, 2007|website=BBC}}</ref>\nThe [[iPod Touch]], a touchscreen device with the media and internet abilities and interface of the iPhone but without the ability to connect to a cellular network for phone functions or internet access, was released on September 5, 2007. At the same time, Apple significantly dropped the price of the 8&nbsp;GB model (from $599 to $399, still requiring a 2-year contract with AT&T) while discontinuing the 4&nbsp;GB model.<ref>{{cite press release\n |title=Apple Sets iPhone Price at $399 for this Holiday Season\n |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2007/09/05Apple-Sets-iPhone-Price-at-399-for-this-Holiday-Season/\n |date=September 5, 2007\n |publisher=Apple\n |access-date=January 20, 2020\n }}</ref> Apple sold the one millionth iPhone five days later, or 74 days after the release.<ref>{{cite press release\n |title=Apple Sells One Millionth iPhone\n |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2007/09/10Apple-Sells-One-Millionth-iPhone/\n |date=September 10, 2007\n |publisher=Apple\n |access-date=January 20, 2020\n }}</ref> After receiving \"hundreds of emails...upset\" about the price drop, Apple gave store credit to early adopters.<ref>{{cite web\n |last=Jobs\n |first=Steve\n |title=To all iPhone customers:\n |url=https://www.apple.com/hotnews/openiphoneletter/\n |publisher=Apple\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070908223628/http://www.apple.com/hotnews/openiphoneletter/ |archivedate=September 8, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nA 16&nbsp;GB model was released on February 5, 2008 for $499, the original launch price of the 4&nbsp;GB model.<ref>{{cite press release\n |title=Apple Adds New iPhone & iPod touch Models\n |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2008/02/05Apple-Adds-New-iPhone-iPod-touch-Models/\n |date=February 5, 2008\n |publisher=Apple\n |access-date=January 20, 2020\n }}</ref> Apple released an [[iOS SDK|SDK]] on March 6, 2008, allowing developers to create the apps that would be available starting in iPhone OS [[iOS version history|version 2.0]], a free upgrade for iPhone users. On June 9, Apple announced the [[iPhone 3G]], which began shipping July 11.<ref>{{cite press release\n |title=Apple Introduces the New iPhone 3G\n |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2008/06/09Apple-Introduces-the-New-iPhone-3G/\n |date=June 9, 2008\n |publisher=Apple\n |access-date=January 20, 2020\n }}</ref> The original iPhone was discontinued on July 15; total sales volume came to 6,124,000 units.\n\n==Software==\n\n{{See also|iOS|iPhone OS 1|iPhone OS 2|iPhone OS 3}}\n\nAt the time of its unveiling in January, Steve Jobs claimed: \"iPhone runs OS X\" and runs \"desktop class applications\",<ref>{{cite web |first=Ryan |last=Block |authorlink=Ryan Block |title=Live from Macworld 2007: Steve Jobs keynote |url=https://www.engadget.com/2007/01/09/live-from-macworld-2007-steve-jobs-keynote/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=January 9, 2007 |accessdate=April 1, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324084725/https://www.engadget.com/2007/01/09/live-from-macworld-2007-steve-jobs-keynote/ |archivedate=March 24, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Mic |last=Wright |title=The original iPhone announcement annotated: Steve Jobs\u2019 genius meets Genius |url=https://thenextweb.com/apple/2015/09/09/genius-annotated-with-genius/ |website=The Next Web |date=September 9, 2015 |accessdate=April 1, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401232647/https://thenextweb.com/apple/2015/09/09/genius-annotated-with-genius/ |archivedate=April 1, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> but at the time of the iPhone's release, the operating system was renamed \"iPhone OS\".<ref>{{cite web |title=iOS: A visual history |url=https://www.theverge.com/2011/12/13/2612736/ios-history-iphone-ipad |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=September 16, 2013 |accessdate=April 1, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170412015548/http://www.theverge.com/2011/12/13/2612736/ios-history-iphone-ipad |archivedate=April 12, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe original iPhone supported three major versions of the operating system before it was discontinued: [[iPhone OS 1]], [[iPhone OS 2|2]], and [[iPhone OS 3|3]]. The last update the original iPhone received was iPhone OS 3.1.3. It never got the full [[iPhone OS 3]] feature set because [[iOS version history#iPhone OS 3|iPhone OS 3.2]] was intended for [[iPad (1st generation)|the iPad]].\n===Software history===\n{{main | iOS version history}}\nThe original operating system for the original iPhone, [[iPhone OS 1]], featured [[Visual Voicemail]], [[multi-touch]] gestures, [[HTML]] [[HTML email|email]], Apple's [[Safari (web browser)|Safari]] web browser, [[Conversation threading|threaded]] [[text messaging]], an \"[[iPod]]\" music and video player app, a dedicated [[YouTube]] [[YouTube#Platforms|app]] and a [[Google Maps#Mobile app|Maps app]] powered by [[Google Maps]]. It also included basic Phone/contacts, Calendar, Photos, Stocks, Weather, Clock, Calculator, Notes, and Settings apps. However, many features like [[Multimedia Messaging Service|MMS]], [[Mobile app|apps]], and [[cut, copy, and paste|copy and paste]] were not supported at release, leading hackers [[iOS jailbreaking|jailbreaking]] their phones to add these features. Software updates from Apple gradually added these functions.\n\nA v1.1 update alongside the introduction of the [[iPod Touch (1st generation)|iPod Touch]] in September 2007 included an [[iTunes Store]] app that was the first new app to be added to the system.\n\n[[iPhone OS 2]] was released on July 11, 2008, at the same time as the release of the [[iPhone 3G]], and introduced Apple's [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]] supporting native [[iOS SDK|third-party applications]], [[Microsoft Exchange Server|Microsoft Exchange]] support,<ref>{{cite web |title=Exchange ActiveSync On Your iPhone 2.0 |url=https://www.imore.com/walkthrough-exchange-activesync-on-your-iphone-20 |website=iMore |accessdate=January 18, 2019}}</ref> [[push e-mail]], and other enhancements.\n\n[[iPhone OS 3]] was released on June 17, 2009 alongside the [[iPhone 3GS]], and introduced copy and paste functionality, [[Spotlight (software)|Spotlight search]] for the [[SpringBoard|home screen]], and new features for the YouTube app. iPhone OS 3 was available for the original iPhone as well as the iPhone 3G and 3GS. However, not all features of iPhone OS 3 (like MMS in the [[Messages (Apple)|Messages]] app) were supported on the original iPhone.\n\niPhone OS 3.1.3 was the last version of iPhone OS (now [[iOS]]) to be released for this phone, which never got the full iPhone OS 3 feature set because [[iOS version history#iPhone OS 3|iPhone OS 3.2]] was intended for [[iPad (1st generation)|the iPad]].\n\n==Reception==\nThe original iPhone received positive reviews. Only four writers were given review models of the original iPhone:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/06/25/pogue-iphone-reminisce/|title=Original iPhone's First Four Reviewers Reminisce About Getting Their Hands on It for the First Time|first=Eric|last=Slivka|website=www.macrumors.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/the-iphone-turns-10/|title=It had us at \"Hello\": The iPhone turns 10|first1=CBS News|last1=June 25|first2=|last2=2017|first3=9:08|last3=Am|website=www.cbsnews.com}}</ref> [[David Pogue]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news\n |author=[[David Pogue]]\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/27/technology/circuits/27pogue.html?ex=1340596800&en=d00bbea4b9e0ece6&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink\n |title=The iPhone Matches Most of Its Hype\n |date=June 27, 2007\n |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> [[Walt Mossberg]] of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'',<ref>{{cite news\n |author=[[Walt Mossberg]]\n |url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB118289311361649057.html\n |title=Testing Out the iPhone\n |date=June 27, 2007\n |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref> [[Steven Levy]] of ''[[Newsweek]]'',<ref>{{cite news\n |author=[[Steven Levy]]\n |url=http://www.newsweek.com/first-look-test-driving-iphone-102625\n |title=First Look: Test Driving the iPhone\n |date=June 26, 2007\n |work=[[Newsweek]]}}</ref> and [[Ed Baig]] of ''[[USA Today]]''.<ref>{{cite news\n |author=[[Ed Baig]]\n |url=https://www.usatoday.com/tech/columnist/edwardbaig/2007-06-26-iphone-review_N.htm\n |title=iPhone Review\n |date=June 26, 2007\n |work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' and ''The Wall Street Journal'' published positive, but cautious, reviews of the iPhone, their primary criticisms being the relatively slow speed of the [[AT&T]]'s 2.5G [[EDGE]] network and the phone's inability to connect using [[3G]] services. ''The Wall Street Journal''{{'}}s technology columnist, Walt Mossberg, concluded that \"despite some flaws and feature omissions, the iPhone is, on balance, a beautiful and breakthrough handheld computer.\"<ref>{{cite news\n |url = http://www.theaustralian.com.au/australian-it/iphone-rush-despite-mixed-reviews/story-e6frgalx-1111113871271\n |title = iPhone rush despite mixed reviews\n |date = July 3, 2007\n |work = The Australian\n |accessdate = February 1, 2007}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine named it the [[Invention of the Year]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite news\n |author=Grossman, Lev\n |title=Invention Of the Year: The iPhone\n |url=http://www.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,1678581,00.html\n |date=October 31, 2007\n |accessdate=June 6, 2008\n |work=Time\n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615155450/http://www.time.com/time/business/article/0%2C8599%2C1678581%2C00.html \n |archivedate=June 15, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n''Mobile Gazette'' reported that whilst the iPhone has many impressive points, it equally has many bad ones too, noting the lack of 3G, [[Multimedia Messaging Service|MMS]], third-party applications, and its weak camera without autofocus and flash.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mobilegazette.com/2007-review-07x12x12.htm|title=2007 in Review: The Good, the Bad and the Ugly|date=November 19, 2007|website=Mobile Gazette}}</ref>\n\n[[File:IPhone First Generation 8GB (3677961514).jpg|thumb|An 8GB iPhone 2G.|152px]]\n\n==Timeline of models==\n{{Timeline of iPhone models}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Apple Inc.}}\n* [[History of iPhone]]\n* [[List of iOS devices]]\n* [[Comparison of smartphones]]\n* [[Apple Newton]]\n*[[300-page iPhone bill]]\n{{clear right}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|IPhone (original)|lcfirst=yes}}\n*{{Official website|www.apple.com/iphone|iPhone}} \u2013 official site\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-new | creation}}\n{{S-ttl | title = iPhone | years = 1st generation}}\n{{S-aft | after  = [[iPhone 3G]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{iOS}}\n{{Apple hardware since 1998}}\n{{Apple}}\n\n[[Category:IPhone|*]]\n[[Category:IOS|iPhone 1]]\n[[Category:Mobile phones introduced in 2007]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2007]]\n[[Category:Obsolete technologies]]\n[[Category:Discontinued smartphones]]\n", "text_old": "{{lower case}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox mobile phone\n| name = iPhone\n| logo = IPhonelogo.svg\n| logosize = 200px\n| image =iPhone 1st Gen.svg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| caption =\n| developer = [[Apple Inc.]]\n| manufacturer = [[Foxconn]] ([[contract manufacturer]])<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/iphone-manufacturer-to-pay-family-of-dead-worker/ \n |title=iPh