{"title_page": "Mark Holton", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mark Holton\n| image              = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1958|04|2}}\n| birth_place        = [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]], United States\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 1983\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Mark Douglas Holton''' (born April 2, 1958) is an American actor, best known for portraying Francis Buxton in ''[[Pee-wee's Big Adventure]]'' (1985), Chubby in the ''[[Teen Wolf]]'' film series and Ozzie Jones in ''[[Leprechaun (film)|Leprechaun]]'' (1993) and ''[[Leprechaun Returns]]'' (2018).\n\n==Early life==\nHolton was born in [[Oklahoma City]]. He graduated from Okmulgee High School in 1976. He attended [[Northeastern State University]] in [[Tahlequah, Oklahoma]].\n\n==Career==\nHolton's professional breakthrough came with the role of Francis Buxton, [[Pee-Wee Herman]]'s nemesis in the blockbuster comedy ''[[Pee-wee's Big Adventure]]'' (1985).<ref name= Barsanti>{{cite book| last= Barsanti| first= Chris| year= 2010| title= Filmology: A Movie-A-Day Guide to the Movies You Need to Know| publisher= Adams Media Corporation| isbn= 978-1-4405-0753-3| page= 256}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Martinez |first1=Kiko |title=Still Claiming Pee-wee 30 Years Later: Mark Holton Reminisces About Playing Francis Buxton |url=https://www.sacurrent.com/sanantonio/still-claiming-pee-wee-30-years-later-mark-holton-reminisces-about-playing-francis-buxton/Content?oid=2458502 |website=SACurrent.com |publisher=[[San Antonio Current]] |accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref> He found further fame as high school basketball player Chubby in the werewolf comedies ''[[Teen Wolf]]'' (1985) and ''[[Teen Wolf Too]]'' (1987).<ref>{{cite web |last1=James |first1=Caryn |title=Film: 'Teen Wolf Too,' Family Curse |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/20/movies/film-teen-wolf-too-family-curse.html |website=NYTimes.com |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sharp |first1=Brian |title=What The \u2018Teen Wolf\u2019 Cast And Crew Have Been Up To Since The \u201980s |url=https://uproxx.com/movies/teen-wolf-where-are-they-now/ |website=Uproxx.com |publisher=[[Uproxx]] |accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref> His mainstream visibility grew with supporting roles in ''[[The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad!]]'' (1988), ''[[A League of Their Own]]'' (1992), ''[[My Life (film)|My Life]]'' (1993) and ''[[Little Giants]]'' (1994).\n\nHolton has been equally prolific in television, performing in episodes of ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'', ''[[Seinfeld]]'', ''[[MacGyver (1985 TV series)|MacGyver]]'', ''[[Sledge Hammer!]]'', ''[[Tim and Eric Awesome Show, Great Job!]]'', ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'', ''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]'' and ''[[NYPD Blue]]''. He also makes an appearance in [[The Ramones]]' music video for \"[[Something to Believe In (Ramones song)|Something to Believe In]]\". Following his cameo appearance in ''[[The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle (film)|The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle]]'' (2000), Holton refocused his attention on independent film and television projects. His first leading film role came through the [[direct-to-video]] drama ''[[Gacy (film)|Gacy]]'' (2003), in which he portrayed [[serial killer]] [[John Wayne Gacy]].\n\nHolton retired from performing in the late 2000s.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Godfrey |first1=Alex |title=Meet The Naked Gun's \u2018Hey, It\u2019s Enrico Pallazzo!\u2019 Guy, AKA Mark Holton |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/meet-naked-gun-hey-enrico-pallazzo-guy-aka-mark-holton/ |website=EmpireOnline.com |publisher=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> He made a comeback with a second portrayal of B.M. Fahrtz in ''Tim and Eric Awesome Show Great Job! Awesome 10 Year Anniversary Version, Great Job?'' (2017). He returned to film acting in the made-for-television ''[[Leprechaun Returns]]'' (2018), a direct sequel to the original cult comedy hit ''[[Leprechaun (film)|Leprechaun]]'' (1993), reprising the role of Ozzie from the film.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miska|first1=Brad|title=\u2018Leprechaun Returns\u2019 Poster Climbs Out of the Original Film\u2019s Well [Exclusive]|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3530844/leprechaun-returns-poster-climbs-original-films-well-exclusive/|publisher=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n<!--DO NOT USE ROWSPANS PER WP:FILMOGRAPHY-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Director\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''What's Up, Hideous Sun Demon''\n| Guy\n| Craig Mitchell<br>Robert Clarke\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Webster (TV series)|Webster]]''\n| Various \n| [[Joel Zwick]]\n| TV Series (2 Episodes)\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1985\n| ''[[Pee-wee's Big Adventure]]''\n| Francis Buxton\n| [[Tim Burton]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Teen Wolf]]''\n| Chubby \n| [[Rod Daniel]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=3|1986\n| ''[[My Chauffeur]]''\n| Doughboy\n| [[David Beaird]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Stoogemania]]''\n| Curly's son\n| [[Chuck Workman]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Modern Girls]]''\n| Boss \n| Jerry Kramer\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1987\n| ''[[Teen Wolf Too]]''\n| Chubby\n| Christopher Leitch\n|\n|-\n| ''Under Cover''\n| Denny \n| [[John Stockwell (actor)|John Stockwell]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1988\n| ''[[Sledge Hammer!]]''\n| Governor's Aide\n| Dick Martin\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad!]]''\n| Spectator\n| [[David Zucker (filmmaker)|David Zucker]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1989\n| ''[[Day by Day (American TV series)|Day by Day]]''\n| Proprietor\n| [[Matthew Diamond]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[Easy Wheels]]''\n| Animal\n| David O'Malley\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1990\n| ''[[Superboy (TV series)|Superboy]]''\n| Johnny Casanova\n| [[David Nutter]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''Grandpa''\n| \n| Alan Ruffier\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1991\n| ''[[They Came from Outer Space]]''\n| Frank\n| Dennis Donnelly\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[MacGyver (1985 TV series)|MacGyver]]''\n| A Guard\n| [[Mike Vejar]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[A League of Their Own]]''\n| Older Stilwell\n| [[Penny Marshall]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4|1993\n| ''[[Leprechaun (film)|Leprechaun]]''\n| Ozzie Jones\n| [[Mark Jones (filmmaker)|Mark Jones]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Flying Blind (TV series)|Flying Blind]]''\n| George\n| [[Stan Daniels]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[The Young Indiana Jones Chronicles]]''\n| [[Alexander Woollcott]]\n| Syd Macartney\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[My Life (film)|My Life]]''\n| Sam\n| [[Bruce Joel Rubin]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1994\n| ''[[Seinfeld]]''\n| David\n| [[Tom Cherones]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[Little Giants]]''\n| Mr. Zolteck\n| [[Duwayne Dunham]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=1|1995\n| ''[[Rumpelstiltskin (1996 film)|Rumpelstiltskin]]''\n| Huge Man\n| [[Mark Jones (filmmaker)|Mark Jones]] (2)\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=1|1996\n| ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]''\n| Bolian\n| [[Kim Friedman]] \n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1997\n| ''Hijacking Hollywood''\n| Officer\n| [[Neil Mandt]]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Sister, Sister (TV series)|Sister, Sister]]''\n| Conductor\n| [[Sheldon Epps]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| rowspan=1|2000\n| ''[[The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle (film)|The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle]]''\n| Potato\n| [[Des McAnuff]] \n| \n|-\n| rowspan=1|2001\n| ''[[The Young and the Restless]]''\n| Joe\n| \n| TV Series (2 Episodes)\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2003\n| ''[[Gacy (film)|Gacy]]''\n| [[John Wayne Gacy]]\n| Clive Saunders\n| \n|-\n| ''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]''\n| Sergeant Linn\n| [[Bradford May]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| rowspan=5|2004\n| ''[[NYPD Blue]]''\n| Ned Applebaum\n| [[Jesse Bochco]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[Rock Me Baby (TV series)|Rock Me Baby]]''\n| Johnny Hot-Pants\n| [[Leonard R. Garner Jr.]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[Madhouse (2004 film)|Madhouse]]''\n| Mr.Hansen\n| [[William Butler (director)|William Butler]]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Return to Sender (2004 film)|Return to Sender]]''\n| Joe Charbonic\n| [[Bille August]]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Quintuplets]]''\n| Santa\n| Andy Cadiff\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2006\n| ''[[Hoboken Hollow]]''\n| Weldon Brodrick\n| Glen Stephens\n| \n|-\n| ''Dreamweaver''\n| Death\n| Candance Gosch\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=3|2007\n| ''Jane Doe: How to Fire Your Boss''\n| Rob Ryan\n| [[James A. Contner]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Days of Our Lives]]''\n| Detective Morgan\n| \n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[Tim and Eric Awesome Show, Great Job!]]''\n| B.M. Fahrtz\n| [[Tim Heidecker]]<br>[[Jonathan Krisel]]<br>[[Eric Wareheim]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n|2008\n| ''The Thirst: Blood War''\n| Earl\n| Tom Shell\n|\n|-\n|2017\n| ''Tim and Eric Awesome Show Great Job! Awesome 10 Year Anniversary Version, Great Job?''\n| B.M. Fahrtz\n| [[Tim Heidecker]]<br>[[Jonathan Krisel]]<br>[[Eric Wareheim]]\n| TV Special\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Leprechaun Returns]]''\n| Ozzie Jones\n| Steven Kostanski\n| \n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0392625}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holton, Mark}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Oklahoma City]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mark Holton\n| image              = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1958|04|2}}\n| birth_place        = [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]], United States\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 1983\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Mark Douglas Holton''' (born April 2, 1958) is an American actor, best known for portraying Francis Buxton in ''[[Pee-wee's Big Adventure]]'' (1985), Chubby in the ''[[Teen Wolf]]'' film series and Ozzie Jones in ''[[Leprechaun (film)|Leprechaun]]'' (1993) and ''[[Leprechaun Returns]]'' (2018).\n\n==Early life==\nHolton was born in [[Oklahoma City]]. He graduated from Okmulgee High School in 1976. He attended [[Northeastern State University]] in [[Tahlequah, Oklahoma]].\n\n==Career==\nHolton's professional breakthrough came with the role of Francis Buxton, [[Pee-Wee Herman]]'s nemesis in the blockbuster comedy ''[[Pee-wee's Big Adventure]]'' (1985).<ref name= Barsanti>{{cite book| last= Barsanti| first= Chris| year= 2010| title= Filmology: A Movie-A-Day Guide to the Movies You Need to Know| publisher= Adams Media Corporation| isbn= 978-1-4405-0753-3| page= 256}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Martinez |first1=Kiko |title=Still Claiming Pee-wee 30 Years Later: Mark Holton Reminisces About Playing Francis Buxton |url=https://www.sacurrent.com/sanantonio/still-claiming-pee-wee-30-years-later-mark-holton-reminisces-about-playing-francis-buxton/Content?oid=2458502 |website=SACurrent.com |publisher=[[San Antonio Current]] |accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref> He found further fame as high school basketball player Chubby in the werewolf comedies ''[[Teen Wolf]]'' (1985) and ''[[Teen Wolf Too]]'' (1987).<ref>{{cite web |last1=James |first1=Caryn |title=Film: 'Teen Wolf Too,' Family Curse |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/20/movies/film-teen-wolf-too-family-curse.html |website=NYTimes.com |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sharp |first1=Brian |title=What The \u2018Teen Wolf\u2019 Cast And Crew Have Been Up To Since The \u201980s |url=https://uproxx.com/movies/teen-wolf-where-are-they-now/ |website=Uproxx.com |publisher=[[Uproxx]] |accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref> His mainstream visibility grew with supporting roles in ''[[The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad!]]'' (1988), ''[[A League of Their Own]]'' (1992), ''[[My Life (film)|My Life]]'' (1993) and ''[[Little Giants]]'' (1994).\n\nHolton has been equally prolific in television, performing in episodes of ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'', ''[[Seinfeld]]'', ''[[MacGyver (1985 TV series)|MacGyver]]'', ''[[Sledge Hammer!]]'', ''[[Tim and Eric Awesome Show, Great Job!]]'', ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'', ''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]'' and ''[[NYPD Blue]]''. He also makes an appearance in [[The Ramones]]' music video for \"[[Something to Believe In (Ramones song)|Something to Believe In]]\". Following his cameo appearance in ''[[The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle (film)|The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle]]'' (2000), Holton refocused his attention on independent film and television projects. His first leading film role came through the [[direct-to-video]] drama ''[[Gacy (film)|Gacy]]'' (2003), in which he portrayed [[serial killer]] [[John Wayne Gacy]].\n\nHolton retired from performing in the late 2000s.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Godfrey |first1=Alex |title=Meet The Naked Gun's \u2018Hey, It\u2019s Enrico Pallazzo!\u2019 Guy, AKA Mark Holton |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/meet-naked-gun-hey-enrico-pallazzo-guy-aka-mark-holton/ |website=EmpireOnline.com |publisher=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> He made a comeback with a second portrayal of B.M. Fahrtz in ''Tim and Eric Awesome Show Great Job! Awesome 10 Year Anniversary Version, Great Job?'' (2017). He returned to film acting in the made-for-television ''[[Leprechaun Returns]]'' (2018), a direct sequel to the original film, reprising the role of Ozzie from the cult comedy hit ''[[Leprechaun (film)|Leprechaun]]'' (1993).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miska|first1=Brad|title=\u2018Leprechaun Returns\u2019 Poster Climbs Out of the Original Film\u2019s Well [Exclusive]|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3530844/leprechaun-returns-poster-climbs-original-films-well-exclusive/|publisher=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n<!--DO NOT USE ROWSPANS PER WP:FILMOGRAPHY-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Director\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''What's Up, Hideous Sun Demon''\n| Guy\n| Craig Mitchell<br>Robert Clarke\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Webster (TV series)|Webster]]''\n| Various \n| [[Joel Zwick]]\n| TV Series (2 Episodes)\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1985\n| ''[[Pee-wee's Big Adventure]]''\n| Francis Buxton\n| [[Tim Burton]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Teen Wolf]]''\n| Chubby \n| [[Rod Daniel]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=3|1986\n| ''[[My Chauffeur]]''\n| Doughboy\n| [[David Beaird]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Stoogemania]]''\n| Curly's son\n| [[Chuck Workman]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Modern Girls]]''\n| Boss \n| Jerry Kramer\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1987\n| ''[[Teen Wolf Too]]''\n| Chubby\n| Christopher Leitch\n|\n|-\n| ''Under Cover''\n| Denny \n| [[John Stockwell (actor)|John Stockwell]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1988\n| ''[[Sledge Hammer!]]''\n| Governor's Aide\n| Dick Martin\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad!]]''\n| Spectator\n| [[David Zucker (filmmaker)|David Zucker]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1989\n| ''[[Day by Day (American TV series)|Day by Day]]''\n| Proprietor\n| [[Matthew Diamond]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[Easy Wheels]]''\n| Animal\n| David O'Malley\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1990\n| ''[[Superboy (TV series)|Superboy]]''\n| Johnny Casanova\n| [[David Nutter]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''Grandpa''\n| \n| Alan Ruffier\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1991\n| ''[[They Came from Outer Space]]''\n| Frank\n| Dennis Donnelly\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[MacGyver (1985 TV series)|MacGyver]]''\n| A Guard\n| [[Mike Vejar]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[A League of Their Own]]''\n| Older Stilwell\n| [[Penny Marshall]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4|1993\n| ''[[Leprechaun (film)|Leprechaun]]''\n| Ozzie Jones\n| [[Mark Jones (filmmaker)|Mark Jones]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Flying Blind (TV series)|Flying Blind]]''\n| George\n| [[Stan Daniels]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[The Young Indiana Jones Chronicles]]''\n| [[Alexander Woollcott]]\n| Syd Macartney\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[My Life (film)|My Life]]''\n| Sam\n| [[Bruce Joel Rubin]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1994\n| ''[[Seinfeld]]''\n| David\n| [[Tom Cherones]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[Little Giants]]''\n| Mr. Zolteck\n| [[Duwayne Dunham]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=1|1995\n| ''[[Rumpelstiltskin (1996 film)|Rumpelstiltskin]]''\n| Huge Man\n| [[Mark Jones (filmmaker)|Mark Jones]] (2)\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=1|1996\n| ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]''\n| Bolian\n| [[Kim Friedman]] \n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1997\n| ''Hijacking Hollywood''\n| Officer\n| [[Neil Mandt]]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Sister, Sister (TV series)|Sister, Sister]]''\n| Conductor\n| [[Sheldon Epps]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| rowspan=1|2000\n| ''[[The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle (film)|The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle]]''\n| Potato\n| [[Des McAnuff]] \n| \n|-\n| rowspan=1|2001\n| ''[[The Young and the Restless]]''\n| Joe\n| \n| TV Series (2 Episodes)\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2003\n| ''[[Gacy (film)|Gacy]]''\n| [[John Wayne Gacy]]\n| Clive Saunders\n| \n|-\n| ''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]''\n| Sergeant Linn\n| [[Bradford May]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| rowspan=5|2004\n| ''[[NYPD Blue]]''\n| Ned Applebaum\n| [[Jesse Bochco]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[Rock Me Baby (TV series)|Rock Me Baby]]''\n| Johnny Hot-Pants\n| [[Leonard R. Garner Jr.]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[Madhouse (2004 film)|Madhouse]]''\n| Mr.Hansen\n| [[William Butler (director)|William Butler]]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Return to Sender (2004 film)|Return to Sender]]''\n| Joe Charbonic\n| [[Bille August]]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Quintuplets]]''\n| Santa\n| Andy Cadiff\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2006\n| ''[[Hoboken Hollow]]''\n| Weldon Brodrick\n| Glen Stephens\n| \n|-\n| ''Dreamweaver''\n| Death\n| Candance Gosch\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=3|2007\n| ''Jane Doe: How to Fire Your Boss''\n| Rob Ryan\n| [[James A. Contner]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Days of Our Lives]]''\n| Detective Morgan\n| \n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[Tim and Eric Awesome Show, Great Job!]]''\n| B.M. Fahrtz\n| [[Tim Heidecker]]<br>[[Jonathan Krisel]]<br>[[Eric Wareheim]]\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n|2008\n| ''The Thirst: Blood War''\n| Earl\n| Tom Shell\n|\n|-\n|2017\n| ''Tim and Eric Awesome Show Great Job! Awesome 10 Year Anniversary Version, Great Job?''\n| B.M. Fahrtz\n| [[Tim Heidecker]]<br>[[Jonathan Krisel]]<br>[[Eric Wareheim]]\n| TV Special\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Leprechaun Returns]]''\n| Ozzie Jones\n| Steven Kostanski\n| \n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0392625}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holton, Mark}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Oklahoma City]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n", "name_user": "All Hallow's Wraith", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Holton"}
{"title_page": "Lukas Biewald", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Lukas Biewald\n|image =Lukas Biewald Poptech.jpg\n|caption =Biewald speaking at PopTech 2011.\n}}\n\n'''Lukas Biewald''' (born 1981 in Massachusetts) is an entrepreneur living in San Francisco, California. Biewald was the founder and CEO of [[Figure Eight Inc.]] (formerly CrowdFlower) \u2014 an Internet company that collects training data for machine learning \u2014 which he co-founded in December 2007 with Chris Van Pelt.<ref>{{cite news|last=Barret|first=Victoria|title=Dolores Labs Vets Web Sites On The Cheap|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2009/0330/048-you-know-it.html|accessdate=16 April 2011|newspaper=Forbes|date=11 March 2009}}</ref>  In 2019, Biewald sold Figure Eight to [[Appen_(company)|Appen]] for 300 million dollars.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ha|first=Anthony|title=Appen acquires Figure Eight for up to $300M, bringing two data annotation companies together|url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/03/10/appen-acquires-figure-eight/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Biewald founded Weights and Biases, a company that creates developer tools for machine learning.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ha|first=Anthony|title=Weights & Biases raises $5M to build development tools for machine learning|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/05/31/weights-biases-raises-5m-to-build-development-tools-for-machine-learning/}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nPrior to co-founding Figure Eight, Biewald was a Senior Scientist and Manager within the Ranking and Management Team at [[Powerset (company)|Powerset]], a natural language search technology company later acquired by [[Microsoft]].\n\nFrom 2005 to 2006, Biewald led the Search Relevance Team for [[Yahoo! Japan]], where he focused on using statistical machine learning approaches to improve the web search ranking function for international markets.\n\n=== Awards and Honors ===\n\nIn 2010, he won the Netexplorateur Prize<ref>{{cite web|title=Lukas BIEWALD / Add value to the world|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PcAYm0HfE34&feature=player_embedded|publisher=Netexplorateur|accessdate=17 April 2011|date=4 May 2010}}</ref> for creating the GiveWork iPhone app,<ref>{{cite web|title=GiveWork - Dolores Labs - platform iOS 3.0 - version 1.1|date=3 February 2010|url=https://itunes.apple.com/app/give-work/id329928364?mt=8}}</ref> which allows users to perform small tasks that assist refugees and people in developing countries. Later that year, ''Inc. Magazine'' included Biewald and Van Pelt on its list of the Top 30 Entrepreneurs Under 30.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lagorio|first=Christine|title=Lukas Biewald and Chris Van Pelt, Founders of Crowdflower|url=http://www.inc.com/30under30/2010/profile-lukas-biewald-chris-van-pelt-crowdflower.html|accessdate=17 April 2011|newspaper=Inc. Magazine|date=19 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nBiewald and Van Pelt launched CrowdFlower as a product of Dolores Labs at TechCrunch50<ref>{{cite web |title=The TechCrunch50 Finalists 2009 |url=http://www.techcrunch50.com/2009/companies/ |publisher=TechCrunch|accessdate=17 April 2011}}</ref> in 2009, where the company placed as a finalist.\n\nHe is the author of several academic papers<ref>{{cite journal|last=Biewald|first=Lukas|title=Massive multiplayer human computation for fun, money, and survival|journal=XRDS: Crossroads, the ACM Magazine for Students|volume=17|issue=2|pages=10|doi=10.1145/1869086.1869093|url=http://xrds.acm.org/article.cfm?aid=1869093|accessdate=16 April 2011|year=2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Scalable crisis relief: Crowdsourced SMS translation and categorization with Mission 4636|url=http://crowdflower.com/images/marketing/Haiti2010.pdf|publisher=ACM DEV \u201910|accessdate=16 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110206111110/http://crowdflower.com/images/marketing/Haiti2010.pdf|archive-date=6 February 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ensuring quality in crowdsourced search relevance evaluation: The effects of training question distribution|url=http://crowdflower.com/images/marketing/SIGIRpaper.pdf|publisher=SIGIR \u201910|accessdate=16 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224154657/https://crowdflower.com/images/marketing/SIGIRpaper.pdf|archive-date=24 December 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>  on applications of [[crowdsourcing]], as well as a chapter on crowdsourcing gender and age stereotypes<ref>{{cite book|title=Beautiful Data|year=2009|publisher=O'Reilly Media|isbn=978-0-596-15711-1|page=384|url=http://oreilly.com/catalog/9780596157128#toc}}</ref> in O'Reilly Media's ''Beautiful Data'' that he co-authored with Brendan O'Connor.\n\n=== Academic Life ===\n\nBiewald holds an MS in Computer Science and a BS in Mathematics from Stanford University.\n\nWhile pursuing his Master's in Computer Science at Stanford University, Biewald won the California Institute of Technology Turing Tournament.<ref>[http://www.stanforddaily.com/2004/01/07/grad-student-wins-10000-game-theory-competition/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120202938/http://www.stanforddaily.com/2004/01/07/grad-student-wins-10000-game-theory-competition/ |date=November 20, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biewald, Lukas}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:American computer programmers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Boston]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Lukas Biewald\n|image =Lukas Biewald Poptech.jpg\n|caption =Biewald speaking at PopTech 2011.\n}}\n\n'''Lukas Biewald''' (born 1981 in Massachusetts) is an entrepreneur living in San Francisco, California. Biewald was the founder and CEO of [[Figure Eight Inc.]] (formerly CrowdFlower) \u2014 an Internet company that collects training data for machine learning \u2014 which he co-founded in December 2007 with Chris Van Pelt.<ref>{{cite news|last=Barret|first=Victoria|title=Dolores Labs Vets Web Sites On The Cheap|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2009/0330/048-you-know-it.html|accessdate=16 April 2011|newspaper=Forbes|date=11 March 2009}}</ref>  In 2019, Biewald sold Figure Eight to [[Appen_(company)|Appen]] for 300 million dollars.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ha|first=Anthony|title=Appen acquires Figure Eight for up to $300M, bringing two data annotation companies together|url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/03/10/appen-acquires-figure-eight/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Biewald founded Weights and Biases, a company that creates developer tools for machine learning. <ref>{{cite news|last=Ha|first=Anthony|title=Weights & Biases raises $5M to build development tools for machine learning|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/05/31/weights-biases-raises-5m-to-build-development-tools-for-machine-learning/</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nPrior to co-founding Figure Eight, Biewald was a Senior Scientist and Manager within the Ranking and Management Team at [[Powerset (company)|Powerset]], a natural language search technology company later acquired by [[Microsoft]].\n\nFrom 2005 to 2006, Biewald led the Search Relevance Team for [[Yahoo! Japan]], where he focused on using statistical machine learning approaches to improve the web search ranking function for international markets.\n\n=== Awards and Honors ===\n\nIn 2010, he won the Netexplorateur Prize<ref>{{cite web|title=Lukas BIEWALD / Add value to the world|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PcAYm0HfE34&feature=player_embedded|publisher=Netexplorateur|accessdate=17 April 2011|date=4 May 2010}}</ref> for creating the GiveWork iPhone app,<ref>{{cite web|title=GiveWork - Dolores Labs - platform iOS 3.0 - version 1.1|date=3 February 2010|url=https://itunes.apple.com/app/give-work/id329928364?mt=8}}</ref> which allows users to perform small tasks that assist refugees and people in developing countries. Later that year, ''Inc. Magazine'' included Biewald and Van Pelt on its list of the Top 30 Entrepreneurs Under 30.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lagorio|first=Christine|title=Lukas Biewald and Chris Van Pelt, Founders of Crowdflower|url=http://www.inc.com/30under30/2010/profile-lukas-biewald-chris-van-pelt-crowdflower.html|accessdate=17 April 2011|newspaper=Inc. Magazine|date=19 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nBiewald and Van Pelt launched CrowdFlower as a product of Dolores Labs at TechCrunch50<ref>{{cite web |title=The TechCrunch50 Finalists 2009 |url=http://www.techcrunch50.com/2009/companies/ |publisher=TechCrunch|accessdate=17 April 2011}}</ref> in 2009, where the company placed as a finalist.\n\nHe is the author of several academic papers<ref>{{cite journal|last=Biewald|first=Lukas|title=Massive multiplayer human computation for fun, money, and survival|journal=XRDS: Crossroads, the ACM Magazine for Students|volume=17|issue=2|pages=10|doi=10.1145/1869086.1869093|url=http://xrds.acm.org/article.cfm?aid=1869093|accessdate=16 April 2011|year=2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Scalable crisis relief: Crowdsourced SMS translation and categorization with Mission 4636|url=http://crowdflower.com/images/marketing/Haiti2010.pdf|publisher=ACM DEV \u201910|accessdate=16 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110206111110/http://crowdflower.com/images/marketing/Haiti2010.pdf|archive-date=6 February 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ensuring quality in crowdsourced search relevance evaluation: The effects of training question distribution|url=http://crowdflower.com/images/marketing/SIGIRpaper.pdf|publisher=SIGIR \u201910|accessdate=16 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224154657/https://crowdflower.com/images/marketing/SIGIRpaper.pdf|archive-date=24 December 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>  on applications of [[crowdsourcing]], as well as a chapter on crowdsourcing gender and age stereotypes<ref>{{cite book|title=Beautiful Data|year=2009|publisher=O'Reilly Media|isbn=978-0-596-15711-1|page=384|url=http://oreilly.com/catalog/9780596157128#toc}}</ref> in O'Reilly Media's ''Beautiful Data'' that he co-authored with Brendan O'Connor.\n\n=== Academic Life ===\n\nBiewald holds an MS in Computer Science and a BS in Mathematics from Stanford University.\n\nWhile pursuing his Master's in Computer Science at Stanford University, Biewald won the California Institute of Technology Turing Tournament.<ref>[http://www.stanforddaily.com/2004/01/07/grad-student-wins-10000-game-theory-competition/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120202938/http://www.stanforddaily.com/2004/01/07/grad-student-wins-10000-game-theory-competition/ |date=November 20, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biewald, Lukas}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:American computer programmers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Boston]]\n", "name_user": "Grimes2", "label": "safe", "comment": "format cite template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lukas_Biewald"}
